s incised with delicate scars similar to those worn by women like Tschabante N’dormoudi (pictured here). River silt also plays an important role in men’s initiation rites; it is rubbed onto their skins to encourage their fertilizing power. Many Bétamarribé call the markings on their homes ikerii or “the house’s scar,” and they even treat each house as it were a living being; they give human-related names and associations to many of its various parts. One elder said that his tata was made from “flesh” (earth), “bones” (pebbles), and “blood” (water) just like a human is, and when its owner dies “we say that it is a man and it is dead.”\"'),(8192,67,2,51,0,'Image'),(8190,67,2,46,0,'Unknown'),(8191,67,2,42,0,'JPEG'),(8189,67,2,47,0,'Lars Krutak'),(8185,67,2,39,0,'Lars Krutak'),(8186,67,2,48,0,'http://www.larskrutak.com/'),(5527,68,2,38,0,'<kml xmlns=\"http://earth.google.com/kml/2.0\"><Folder><name>OpenLayers export</name><description>Exported on Sat Nov 10 2012 15:04:15 GMT-0800 (PST)</description><Placemark><name>OpenLayers.Feature.Vector_160</name><description>No description available</description><Point><coordinates>258002.04192256,1207143.5890077</coordinates></Point></Placemark></Folder></kml>|5|722739.17383174|1045708.5852919|ghyb\r\nAfrica'),(5525,68,2,51,0,'Image'),(5526,68,2,43,0,'Unknown'),(5520,68,2,45,0,'Lars Krutak'),(5519,68,2,48,0,'http://www.larskrutak.com/'),(5518,68,2,39,0,'Lars Krutak'),(8187,67,2,45,0,'Lars Krutak'),(8188,67,2,40,0,'2002'),(5546,66,2,49,0,'Benin, 21st Century, cultural'),(5684,70,2,43,0,'Unknown'),(5685,70,2,38,0,'<kml xmlns=\"http://earth.google.com/kml/2.0\"><Folder><name>OpenLayers export</name><description>Exported on Sat Nov 10 2012 15:05:22 GMT-0800 (PST)</description><Placemark><name>OpenLayers.Feature.Vector_160</name><description>No description available</description><Point><coordinates>2072922.8412731441,-289799.1727207881</coordinates></Point></Placemark></Folder></kml>|4|2053354.9620349|-221311.59538681|ghyb\r\nAfrica'),