st Century, methodological'),(4274,61,3,74,0,'8'),(4275,61,3,75,0,'3'),(4276,61,3,77,0,'a:9:{s:8:\"FileName\";s:36:\"f591f7712658e72e408fe7734521568f.jpg\";s:12:\"FileDateTime\";i:1352578518;s:8:\"FileSize\";i:23768;s:8:\"FileType\";i:2;s:8:\"MimeType\";s:10:\"image/jpeg\";s:13:\"SectionsFound\";s:5:\"APP12\";s:8:\"COMPUTED\";a:4:{s:4:\"html\";s:24:\"width=\"256\" height=\"280\"\";s:6:\"Height\";i:280;s:5:\"Width\";i:256;s:7:\"IsColor\";i:1;}s:7:\"Company\";s:5:\"Ducky\";s:4:\"Info\";s:1:\"\";}'),(4277,61,3,76,0,'FileName:f591f7712658e72e408fe7734521568f.jpg\nFileDateTime:1352578518\nFileSize:23768\nFileType:2\nMimeType:image/jpeg\nSectionsFound:APP12\nCOMPUTED:\n	html:width=\"256\" height=\"280\"\n	Height:280\n	Width:256\n	IsColor:1\n\nCompany:Ducky\nInfo:\n'),(4278,61,3,73,0,'280'),(4279,61,3,72,0,'256'),(8216,92,2,48,0,'Lars Krutak'),(8217,92,2,45,0,'http://www.larskrutak.com/'),(8218,92,2,40,0,'2002'),(8219,92,2,47,0,'Lars Krutak'),(8220,92,2,46,0,'Unknown'),(8221,92,2,42,0,'JPEG'),(8222,92,2,51,0,'Image'),(8223,92,2,43,0,'Unknown'),(8224,92,2,38,0,'<kml xmlns=\"http://earth.google.com/kml/2.0\"><Folder><name>OpenLayers export</name><description>Exported on Wed Nov 28 2012 16:43:24 GMT-0800 (PST)</description><Placemark><name>OpenLayers.Feature.Vector_160</name><description>No description available</description><Point><coordinates>169946.58535031593,1187575.7097693298</coordinates></Point></Placemark></Folder></kml>|5|781442.8115466|629891.1514783|ghyb\r\nAfrica'),(8225,92,2,7,0,'Photo'),(8226,92,2,10,0,'256 x 280 '),(8213,92,2,49,0,'Benin, 21st Century, cultural'),(8214,92,2,41,0,'\"In Bétamarribé iconography, crisscross patterns (like the letter X) and ribbed designs that resemble the raised scar patterns seen on men’s chests are symbols of Fayenfe, the god of war and death. This god serves as the patron deity for persons who have come in close or frequent contact with death – tomb diggers, warriors, and certain healers. Fayenfe is believed to ease the trauma of death for such persons and to protect them and the community from various dangers associated with the dead. I think that the ribbed and crisscross patterns carved into the chests of some Bétamarribé men seem to suggest the idea of a barrier, a protective bar or series of bars that perhaps prevented evil spirits (and death) from entering the human body. Similar signs are also carved into the plastered walls of Bétamarribé houses by men to identify that their patron deity is Fayenfe.\"'),(4293,62,3,74,0,'8'),(4294,62,3,75,0,'3'),(4295,62,3,77,0,'a:51:{s:8:\"FileName\";s:36:\"400f489101003514bec01b89b0ed1162.jpg\";s:12:\"FileDateTime\";i:1352579426;s:8:\"FileSize\";i:26780;s:8:\"FileType\";i:2;s:8:\"MimeType\";s:10:\"image/jpeg\";s:13:\"SectionsFound\";s:28:\"ANY_TAG, IFD0, EXIF, INTEROP\";s:8:\"COMPUTED\";a:6:{s:4:\"html\";s:24:\"width=\"309\" height=\"497\"\";s:6:\"Height\";i:497;s:5:\"Width\";i:309;s:7:\"IsColor\";i:1;s:17:\"ByteOrderMotorola\";i:0;s:15:\"ApertureFNumber\";s:5:\"f/4.0\";}s:16:\"ImageDescription\";s:31:\"                               \";s:4:\"Make\";s:4:\"SONY\";s:5:\"Model\";s:8:\"DSC-F828\";s:11:\"Orientation\";i:1;s:11:\"XResolution\";s:4:\"72/1\";s:11:\"YResolution\";s:4:\"72/1\";s:14:\"ResolutionUnit\";i:2;s:8:\"Software\";s:27:\"ACD Systems Digital Imaging\";s:8:\"DateTime\";s:19:\"2011:03:01 18:22:29\";s:16:\"YCbCrPositioning\";i:1;s:16:\"Exif_IFD_Pointer\";i:256;s:12:\"ExposureTime\";s:7:\"10/2000\";s:7:\"FNumber\";s:5:\"40/10\";s:15:\"ExposureProgram\";i:2;s:15:\"ISOSpeedRatings\";i:64;s:11:\"ExifVersion\";s:4:\"0220\";s:16:\"DateTimeOriginal\";s:19:\"2005:10:23 14:31:36\";s:17:\"DateTimeDigitized\";s:19:\"2005:10:23 14:31:36\";s:23:\"ComponentsConfiguration\";s:4:\"\0\";s:22:\"CompressedBitsPerPixel\";s:3:\"8/1\";s:17:\"ExposureBiasValue\";s:4:\"0/10\";s:16:\"MaxApertureValue\";s:5:\"33/16\";s:12:\"MeteringMode\";i:5;s:11:\"LightSource\";i:0;s:5:\"Flash\";i:24;s:11:\"FocalLength\";s:5:\"71/10\";s:9:\"MakerNote\";s:1566:\"SONY DSC \