ko Pigment Container'),(10146,175,2,49,0,'New Zealand - 19th Century - Cultural'),(10147,175,2,41,0,'The ipu ngarahu is a tattoo pigment (ink) container carved out of wood. The containers were carved by hand and are considered to be very sacred. Every artist had their own unique ipu ngarahu and many of them were very beautiful. \r\n\r\nThe pigment itself was created through a unique processs using the natural resources available to the Maori\'s. \r\n\"The awheto (vegetable caterpillar) was burned in a fire known as an ahi kauri (tattooing fire), then the awe (soot) was mixed with spring water, fish oil, or resin from hinau tree (Elaeocarpus dentatus), mahoe (whitey wood: Melicytus ramiflorus), poroporo (black nightshade: Solanum nigrum), and other plants, then kneaded and formed into small balls called kauri. The ngarahu (pigment) obtained from the caterpillar was used for tattooing the limbs or body, but the pigment was not black enough to be used for facial tattooing. Pukepoto (dark blue earth), a fine dark blue uku (clay), was mixed with resins to form a blue pigment and this was applied to the face of the moko (tattoo) recipient.\"'),(10148,175,2,39,0,'Unknown'),(10149,175,2,45,0,'Museum of New Zealand'),(10150,175,2,40,0,'1800'),(10151,175,2,51,0,'Still Image'),(10152,175,2,38,0,'<kml xmlns=\"http://earth.google.com/kml/2.0\"><Folder><name>OpenLayers export</name><description>Exported on Thu Nov 29 2012 19:30:06 GMT-0800 (PST)</description><Placemark><name>OpenLayers.Feature.Vector_159</name><description>No description available</description><Point><coordinates>19233433.157453,-5289683.4774402</coordinates></Point></Placemark></Folder></kml>|4|19213865.278215|-5101994.7431692|ghyb\r\n'),(10153,175,2,7,0,'Wood Carving'),(10682,191,2,50,0,'The Moko Suite: Moerangi Ratahi'),(11276,148,2,45,0,'CNN.com'),(11274,148,2,39,0,'Unknown'),(11275,148,2,48,0,'youtube.com'),(10218,145,2,10,0,'330 × 426 '),(10232,144,2,43,0,'Unknown'),(10233,144,2,38,0,'<kml xmlns=\"http://ea