0683,191,2,49,0,'New Zealand - 20th Century - Cultural'),(10684,191,2,41,0,'This photo of Moerangi Ratahi shows her traditional Maori ta moko tattoo on her chin. It is not uncommon for women of all ages to have such tattoos in New Zealand despite the unusual location. This photograph was taken for the book Moko: Maori tattooing in the 20th Century, by Michael King, published in 1972.'),(10685,191,2,39,0,'Marti Friedlander'),(10686,191,2,48,0,'Moko: Maori tattooing in the 20th Century'),(10687,191,2,45,0,'Museum of New Zealand'),(10688,191,2,40,0,'1971'),(10689,191,2,51,0,'Still Image'),(10690,191,2,38,0,'<kml xmlns=\"http://earth.google.com/kml/2.0\"><Folder><name>OpenLayers export</name><description>Exported on Thu Nov 29 2012 20:24:30 GMT-0800 (PST)</description><Placemark><name>OpenLayers.Feature.Vector_159</name><description>No description available</description><Point><coordinates>19548311.359043,-4779599.3613203</coordinates></Point></Placemark></Folder></kml>|4|19156953.774277|-4989629.2057617|ghyb\r\n'),(10691,191,2,7,0,'Photograph'),(10819,18,2,39,0,'Mark Kopua'),(10817,18,2,49,0,'New Zealand - 21st Century - Cultural'),(10818,18,2,41,0,'Peha is a mid to lower body tattoo that is generally large in size. They can cover areas from the back all the way down to the buttocks and legs. Although Maori-style tattoos are far more common to be located on the body, they have significantly less cultural importance compared to those located on the face. '),(10816,18,2,50,0,'Peha Lower Body Maori Tattoo'),(10832,17,2,45,0,'history-nz.org'),(10828,17,2,49,0,'New Zealand - 20th Century - Cultural'),(10829,17,2,41,0,'People of the highest ranks in Maori culture all had tattoos and the head/face was considered to be the most sacred part of the body. That is why tattoos like this are still common today.'),(10830,17,2,39,0,'Unknown'),(10831,17,2,48,0,'Alexander Turnbull Library'),(10827,17,2,50,0,'Maori Facial Moko Tattoo'),(10809,19,2,40,0,'1830'),(10810,19,2,47,0,'John Lill