INSERT INTO `omeka_exhibits` VALUES (1,'Africa','<p><img src=\"http://dh101.humanities.ucla.edu/DH101Fall12Lab5/archive/files/7c289e1c676a228e44f3597e51fa9499.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"800\" height=\"215\" /></p>\r\n<p>In the tribes of Africa, body art is not characterized by the traditional ideas of tattooing. The ancient practice of scarification takes place as the dominant form of body art in this region of the world. As an integral part of African culture, the practice involves the use of unique blades to carve intricate, meaningful designs into the skin. Members of these African tribes receive their first scars as a young child, most often as a right of passage, and continue to receive scars as landmarks of maturity.</p>\r\n<p>Dating back to the 14th century, scarification began as representative of tribal culture and ones ancestory. Over time, it has evolved into serving medical purposes as well as personal protection. For example, the introduction of slave trade began a significant shift in the purpose of scarification; some tribes believed they could use the scars as a way to dissuade slave traders from taking them, as they would be too ugly to be of benefit to slave owners. The practice of scarification that still exists today is central to the routes of tribal culture and representing a tradition introduce by generations and generations of ancestors.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>As shown throughout this&nbsp;exhibit, the painful practice of scarification is an extremely important to tradition and element in the culture of African tribes. This exhibit examines the socio-cultural significance, the procedure of scarification, it\'s roles in medical therapy, and contemporary issues surrounding this cultural practice.&nbsp;</p>','Lindsie Levinson',0,1,'','a:1:{s:7:\"default\";a:4:{s:4:\"logo\";s:36:\"5d21e4638d0a8c839b602d42c70b2e48.jpg\";s:17:\"header_background\";N;s:11:\"footer_text\";s:0:\"\";s:24:\"display_footer_copyright\";s:1:\"0\";}}','africa'),(2,'Pacific Islands','<p><img src=\"http://dh101.humanities.ucla.edu/DH101Fall12Lab5/archive/files/b03fb50acd1c4f1cb6430868341725b9.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"800\" height=\"215\" />&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>When it comes to tattoos, the pacific islands feature some of the richest history and traditions. Although each polynesian culture is different, they share many similar practices and methods, all while maintaining their own unique identity. The Maori people of New Zealand often have tattoos covering their entire face, while those in Samoa and Tonga often get tattoos stretching from their knees all the way to their torsos. The designs of the tattoos are far more meaningful than just a cool design &ndash; they tell stories, teach lessons and can even represent an entire family lineage. A design is not just picked out of a book as tattoos are in many places. Instead, the design is crafted with the upmost carefulness in a process that sometimes takes months. Every line and shape carries a specific meaning making tattoos incredibly sacred among the polynesian community.</p>\r\n<p>The original pacific island tattoos were done through a simple process with a common toolset. Using the similar tools, each culture developed their own spiritual and application process which remains to be considered one of the most sacred arts. Even in modern day, many polynesian tattoo artists use the original design of the tools instead of utilizing modern technologies such as the electric tattoo gun. The pride of the polynesians is extremely evident as old traditions are cherished, even in the modern day.</p>\r\n<p>This exhibit covers the unique designs of tattoos in the major polynesian communities of: New Zealand, Samoa and Tonga, as well as some the shared traditions between them all. Through each painful tap, the ink passes on stories from one generation to then next, with the hopes that it will continue on forever.</p>','Daniel Ross',0,1,'','a:1:{s:10:\"minimalist\";a:3:{s:4:\"logo\";N;s:11:\"footer_text\";s:0:\"\";s:24:\"display_footer_copyright\";s:1:\"0\";}}','pacific-islands-and-oceania'),(3,'North America','<p><img src=\"http://dh101.humanities.ucla.edu/DH101Fall12Lab5/archive/files/dc7cfbaa85e559d9819b97defbef0ed5.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"800\" height=\"215\" /> <br />This exhibit provides a deeper look into the cultural and anthropological effects and motivations of body art in North America beginning in the 18th Century. &nbsp;North American body art is so prevalent today that may soon be uncommon to be a young adult who does not sport a tattoo.&nbsp; Ever since European colonialism brought the practice across the Atlantic Ocean, it has thrived in America.&nbsp; Beginning with only designs of Pacific Island influence, the Americas transformed the nature of tattoo designs as well as the technology behind the machinery and the social perception of the industry.&nbsp; The tattoo business exploded in America around the time of the Korean War, followed by the two World Wars.&nbsp; Soldiers became the perfect audience for tattooists, as they strove to represent fraternal and patriotic symbols greater than themselves. Shortly after this inspiration to the industry, women were granted their rights which opened a plethora of new doors.&nbsp; Tattooing took off in America and the social perception was beginning to shift from a practice geared towards the outcasts of society towards a practice suitable for any middle class civilian.&nbsp; Immediately the government put sanctions on the industry to prevent the spread of disease and promote the health of the American people.&nbsp; Not until the late 20<sup>th</sup> Century was tattooing seen in a more acceptable and professional light.&nbsp; Even today the practice is viewed by many as unprofessional and employers take great notice at prospect employees with tattoos.&nbsp; However negatively they are viewed in the workplace and in broader society, new media is make drastic changes to these perceptions.&nbsp; The increase in popularity of religious and joyful tattoos combined with new state of the art technology, the tattoo representation among celebrities and icons, and the renewed spirit of liberalism and individuality in America have pushed the continent to be the face of the tattoo world today.</p>','Matt Fisher',0,1,'','a:1:{s:7:\"seasons\";a:4:{s:11:\"style_sheet\";s:6:\"winter\";s:11:\"footer_text\";s:0:\"\";s:24:\"display_footer_copyright\";s:1:\"0\";s:4:\"logo\";s:36:\"1f27fa0e148d0c5a32ae9628da92c192.jpg\";}}','north-america'),(4,'Asia','<p><img src=\"http://dh101.humanities.ucla.edu/DH101Fall12Lab5/archive/files/7b9a501602365ace0cdf9227d4dbd73b.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"800\" height=\"215\" />&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Tattoo practices in Asia vary between countries as well as cultures within each country. Here, the focus is primarily on Japan and China, both of which have rich histories in body art ranging back thousands of years ago. There are some similarities between the two regions, such as the idea that both countries reveal a tattoo history in which the cultural meaning and traditional tattoo practices have very much changed over the centuries. A key difference, however, is that within the Chinese tribes, the traditional practices have seemed to outlast those of Japan. Furthermore, this exhibit seeks to tell the rich historical story of body art practices in the East.</p>','Wendy Siino',0,1,'',NULL,'asia'),(5,'Middle East','<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><img src=\"http://dh101.humanities.ucla.edu/DH101Fall12Lab5/archive/files/a308f7abcef1c9740658c59fbe6f5e7f.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"800\" height=\"215\" /></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>The Middle East has a rich tradition of body art, both in the form of permanent ink tattoos and the temporary Mehndi markings also seen in southern Asia, that stretches across history. A variety of methodologies to create body art in this region have seen employment from the dawn of civilization and the dynastic Egyptian period to the modern day. Tattoo traditions in particular have endured in the collective culture of tribal societies even as the spread of Islam subdued the propensity toward tattooing in mainstream Middle Eastern society. By examining the trifecta of history, methodology, and anthropology, greater insights into the fascinating and unique elements of Middle Eastern body art may be gleaned - and that is the driving purpose of this exhibit.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Bedouin:</strong> A tribal culture typically associated with Arabia and its environs, where the majority of it resides, the Bedouin have held fast to their traditions of tattooing for a multitude of generations. The word itself stems from the plural form of&nbsp;<em>badaw</em>, which means \"desert dweller\" in Arabic. Bedouin body art favors the application of tattoos to the face, particularly amongst women, coupled with displays of jewelry and other material items that in some sense elevate the entire body as a canvas for artistic expression.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Muslim Diaspora:</strong> With the rise of Islam, specifically the Sunni branch of Islam, the practice of tattooing lost some popularity in the Middle East due to the belief that tattoos mar the flesh and therefore mar the creation of Allah, which can be considered a grevious sin. The Shiite branch appears more relaxed on the issue, although as expected opinions do vary between individuals. Those who strictly forbid tattoos base their opinion on a hadith recorded by Bukhari - \"\"It was narrated that Abu Juhayfah (may Allah be pleased with him) said: &ldquo;The Prophet (peace and blessings of Allah be upon him) cursed the one who does tattoos, and the one who has a tattoo done.\"</p>\r\n<p></p>','Stephen Youts',0,1,'',NULL,'middle-east'),(6,'Europe','<p><img src=\"http://dh101.humanities.ucla.edu/DH101Fall12Lab5/archive/files/9d29cad10b96cbd22d6d218a10dfe821.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"800\" height=\"215\" /></p>\r\n<div class=\"WordSection1\">\r\n<p>The tattoo scene in Europe was originally thought to be a practice that was brought over to the continent after a few voyages to Polynesia.&nbsp; But a big discovery was made recently when hikers found a preserved body in the Otzal Alpes, this man was believed to have lived approximately in the year 3500 BC.&nbsp; This was a large deal because the preserved body had markings that appeared to be tattoos on many of his joints and possibly resemblant to the practice of acupuncture, which also focuses on placing needles on your joints to releave stress in muscles. &nbsp;This discovery sent the European history of tattoos back centuries, yet there is still so much to be explored, starting as early as the 1200 BC with the Celtics going all the way to the beginning of western modernization of tattoos after voyages to Polynesia.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n</div>','Max Sieck',0,1,'','a:1:{s:7:\"seasons\";a:4:{s:11:\"style_sheet\";s:6:\"winter\";s:4:\"logo\";s:36:\"0ba12aa062059340ef84dee850098d0f.gif\";s:11:\"footer_text\";s:0:\"\";s:24:\"display_footer_copyright\";s:1:\"0\";}}','europe');
