INSERT INTO `omeka_items_section_pages` VALUES (40,NULL,4,'','',16),(39,NULL,4,'','',15),(38,NULL,4,'','',14),(37,NULL,4,'','',13),(36,NULL,4,'','',12),(35,NULL,4,'','',11),(34,NULL,4,'','',10),(33,NULL,4,'','',9),(32,184,4,'','',8),(31,160,4,'','',7),(30,161,4,'','',6),(29,162,4,'','',5),(28,125,4,'','',4),(27,128,4,'','',3),(26,22,4,'','',2),(25,121,4,'<p>Samoa is one of the countries with the richest history of tattoos &ndash; what they call tatau or pe\'a. With many traditions lasting over 2000 years, the techniques and tools they use have not changed since the beginning. It is still common for Samoans to receive their tatau by hand using the simple tools called &ldquo;au&rdquo;. The pigment or ink is made of a completely natural recipe consisting of insects, roots and other plants. As the ink is embedded in the skin, one tap at a time, the resulting design proves to be much more than just an artistic piece. Like many polynesian cultures, the Samoan society is lead by chiefs and is defined by rank. The young chiefs participate in a tattooing ceremony generally at the point of puberty. A Samoan unable to endure the extreme pain of tatau are forced to wear their incomplete piece as a symbol of shame for the rest of their life.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>','',1),(273,24,25,'<p>Tattoos such as this one on Brian Kirk portray the significance to a soldier of laying his or her life on the line. &nbsp;Beginning in World War I, US soldiers transformed the cultural significance of body art in America. &nbsp;They understood that they were fighting for something greater than themselves, and sought a new outlook to express their lifelong commitment and dedication to their brothers in arms and their country. &nbsp;The tattoo business boomed in the 1920\'s when soldiers returned from war and painted their bodies to convey their loyalty to the red, white and blue.</p>','<p>Depiction of American soldiers standing bravely after a battle tattooed onto a soldier\'s arm.</p>',1),(272,NULL,24,'','',12),(271,NULL,24,'','',11),(270,NULL,24,'','',10),(269,NULL,24,'','',9),(268,NULL,24,'','',8),(267,1,24,'<div class=\"page\" title=\"Page 1\">\r\n<div class=\"layoutArea\">\r\n<div class=\"column\">\r\n<p><span>\"Tattooing and body modification in general have to be also considered in relation to the issue of intangible heritage. There are many cultures of the world which had a rich tradition in tattooing and because of direct or indirect Western influence they have lost this tradition or it is in the process of extinction. More and more, the body does not reflect any more particular worldviews of particular cultures or societies but uniformized attitudes coming from dominant paradigms. We know that globalization is changing our world and according to this, globalization is also changing the relationship people have with their own bodies. In this article I will focus on two very concrete cases: the Li people in Hainan, in China, and the example of the population in Equatorial Guinea, in west central Africa.\"</span></p>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>','',7),(266,27,24,'<p><span>\"From Southern China the practice spread along the silk-route.</span><span>&nbsp;There have been a few periods in the history of the Far East when tattoos were accepted. Tattooing was mostly associated with the lower classes or the underworld. Though practiced in China for thousands of years, civilized and sophisticated Chinese showed nothing but disdain for it throughout this period. The practice become completely discredited after the Communist takeover in 1949. It was also held in contempt in Japan then greatly influenced by China in this regard.&nbsp;</span><span>This changed in the 18&prime;th century when&nbsp;<a title=\"Artists\" href=\"http://tattootemple.hk/artists\">artists</a>&nbsp;became interested in the art of tattooing. For a period tattoos were very fashionable particularly among workers. The Japanese tattoo style even became the international trendsetter. Prominent Westerners were attracted to the Japanese style and even traveled to Japan to receive the artwork. The introduction of the Japanese style to the west contributed greatly to the short-lived vogue of tattooing among the Western elite at the end of the 19&prime;th century.\"</span></p>','',6),(265,41,24,'<p>This website provides a general overview of the tattooing practices in China, while going into specific detail on the Dai tribe\'s tattoo culture.&nbsp;</p>','',5),(264,42,24,'<p>\"<span>Ancient tattoo art in China has been featured in Chinese literature wherein many Chinese ethnic groups were known to tattoo themselves, since the Zhou Dynasty that was prevalent from 1045 BC to 256 BC. In ancient China tattooing was associated with groups or individual criminals, bandits and gangsters. Also there was a practice of tattooing convicts and slave\'s faces with Chinese characters until the Qing dynasty from 1614 - 1912. Also, according to a famous Chinese legend, the most popular general of the Song dynasty, Yue Fei, had made his mother tattoo the words \'jing zhong bao guo\' (精忠報國) on his back with the help of a sewing needle. The words meant \'repay his country with pure loyalty\' and the mother tattooed them right before he left to join the army.</span>\"</p>','',4),(263,45,24,'<p>\"This paper is a holistic look at the world of tattoo. It covers the history of the practice in three major world regions, Europe, Asia and the Pacific, from the earliest known references to tattooing to modern day tattoo culture that spans the globe. It also provides a discussion of some of the major issues that surround the practice, including such topics as tattooing in relation to the body, authenticity, commodification and meaning, functions, medical and legal concerns and the impact of technological developments on the practice, and the increase in popularity of tattooing in recent decades.\"</p>','',3),(262,NULL,24,'','',2),(261,NULL,24,'','',1),(107,63,11,'','',1),(108,61,12,'','<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>',1),(109,51,12,'','',2),(110,10,12,'','',3),(111,57,12,'','',4),(112,58,12,'','',5),(113,190,12,'','',6),(114,53,12,'','',7),(115,59,12,'','',8),(116,8,12,'','',9),(117,109,12,'','',10),(118,159,12,'','',11),(119,155,12,'','',12),(120,173,12,'','',13),(121,225,12,'','',14),(122,NULL,12,'','',15),(123,NULL,12,'','',16),(124,164,13,'<p><strong>Introduction to the History of tattoos in Europe:</strong></p>\r\n<p>It has been a vey controversial topic whether or not tattooing is a European practice. &nbsp;Many believe that the idea of tattooing arrived in Europe after there were many voyages and Europeans came into contact with those of the Polynesian descent. &nbsp;But there is also a lot of evidence in Greek and Roman writings that say otherwise. &nbsp;The history of tattooing and body art in Europe is one of great interest and through these articles referring to the history of it all you should be able to gather a great bit of knowledge about the topic. &nbsp;Although the much has happened in the history of tattoos, in comparison to what has happened in areas such as Asia, the Pacific Islands, and Africa, the history of tattooing seems small and almost unimportant as much of what is happening in Europe has directly descended from places all over and really only started becoming prevalent in Europe in the late 1800s.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>','',1),(125,257,13,'<p><strong>The History of Westernization:</strong></p>\r\n<p>The westernization of tattoos began in the 16th century with expeditions to Polynesia. &nbsp;While the sailors were on these voyages they were exposed to many Amerindian tribes as well as Polynesians who were both very involved in tattooing and was part of their cultures. &nbsp;When the sailors discovered the practice of the tattoo they became enthralled, many returning home with tattoos. &nbsp;By the late 18th century tattoos had become a sign of high class and royalty. &nbsp;They were incredibly expensive not offered to those of the lower class, but this didn&rsquo;t last long. &nbsp;The US had its first documented tattoo artist in 1840, he was a German immigrant by the name of Martin Hildebrandt, he mainly tattooed the men in the Civil War army.&nbsp; While Europe had its first documented tattoo artist open to the public in 1870s in Liverpool. &nbsp;At this point in time as the tattoo market stimulated, tattoo artist became very popular in major port cities. &nbsp;This is what began the retail market of tattoos in Europe and all over the world and from their the practice of tattoos became an epidemic.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>','<p><strong><br /></strong></p>',2),(126,NULL,13,'','',3),(127,NULL,13,'','',4),(128,NULL,13,'','',5),(129,NULL,13,'','',6),(130,NULL,13,'','',7),(131,NULL,13,'','',8),(132,60,13,'','',9),(133,9,13,'','',10),(134,111,13,'','',11),(135,NULL,13,'','',12),(136,NULL,13,'','',13),(137,NULL,13,'','',14),(138,NULL,13,'','',15),(139,NULL,13,'','',16),(140,43,14,'<p>\"The Dulong women began tattooing their faces in reaction. It was thought that the tattoos would make them uglier and less likely to be raped. This tradition has continued into modern times despite the fact that the Dulong are no longer under attack from neighboring tribes.\"</p>','',1),(141,16,14,'<p>\"Body tattoos may be fashionable and cool these days, but facial tattoos have long been a part of Dulong people\'s culture. Known as \"the facial tattoo tribe\", this Chinese ethnic minority lives by the Dulong River Valley in the northwestern part of SW. Yunnan Province.\"</p>','<div id=\"dublin-core-description\" class=\"element\">\r\n<div class=\"element-text\">&nbsp;</div>\r\n</div>',2),(142,15,14,'<p>This woman of the Derung community reveals a tradtional facial tattoo.</p>','',3),(143,102,14,'<p>\"Facial tattooing is an unique tradition of the&nbsp;<a title=\"\" href=\"http://wiki.china.org.cn/wiki/index.php/Derung\" target=\"_blank\"><span>Derung</span></a>&nbsp;ethnic minority. They live in the mountains of the Nujiang Lisu Autonomous Prefecture of Yunnan Province. Girls used to have their faces tattooed before marriage. But as time goes by, only 41 old women are left to testify about the now extinct practice.\"</p>','',4),(144,103,14,'<p>\"<span>In China\'s southwest, there are 41 old women who have retained their facial tattoos once seen as a symbol of beauty.\"</span></p>','',5),(145,104,14,'<p>\"Jiasong of Derung ethnic group shows her tattooed face in Drung-Nu Autonomous County of Gongshan, southwest China\'s Yunnan Province, Feb. 26, 2006. Jiasong, the last tattooed woman of Derung ethnic group, was forced to got tattoos in 1966. The old custom which brought much pain to Derung girls was abolished in 1967.\"</p>','',6),(146,105,14,'<p>Jiasong, the last Derung woman who was facially tattooed, weaving along the Derung river in her native land.</p>','',7),(147,106,14,'<p>\"Kaifuna, 65 years old,&nbsp;has the traditional Derung tattoo&nbsp;on her face.\"</p>','',8),(148,107,14,'','<p>\"<span>At 98, Lape Nannie worries that her own death would erase from the memory of the living a mysterious image: the dark blue tattoo pricked on her face when she was a child.\"</span></p>',9),(260,NULL,23,'','',8),(259,NULL,23,'','',7),(258,NULL,23,'','',6),(257,117,23,'<p><span>\"Geometric tattoos of a Basadung Li woman, ca. 1930.\"</span></p>','',5),(256,116,23,'<p><span>\"Basadung Li hand and leg tattoos, ca. 1930. It was not appropriate for a Basadung Li woman to have her hands tattooed until she was married.\"</span></p>','',4),(255,115,23,'<p><span>\"Like both the Du Long and the Dai, the art of tattooing among the Li is seen as a rite of passage into maturity and adulthood. A Li girl is tattooed sometime during the ages of 13 or 14. The girl would first be tattooed on the nape of the neck, the throat and on the face. This process would take about four or five days.\"</span></p>','',3),(254,1,23,'<p>\"Tattooing and body modification in general have to be also considered in relation to the issue of intangible heritage. There are many cultures of the world which had a rich tradition in tattooing and because of direct or indirect Western influence they have lost this tradition or it is in the process of extinction. More and more, the body does not reflect any more particular worldviews of particular cultures or societies but uniformized attitudes coming from dominant paradigms. We know that globalization is changing our world and according to this, globalization is also changing the relationship people have with their own bodies. In this article I will focus on two very concrete cases: the Li people in Hainan, in China, and the example of the population in Equatorial Guinea, in west central Africa.\"</p>','',2),(253,44,23,'<p>\"Li tattoos differed greatly among the different Li tribes, and could be easily used to differentiate between a woman of one tribe and another.\"</p>','',1),(181,70,17,'','',1),(182,71,17,'','',2),(183,68,17,'','',3),(184,72,17,'','',4),(185,36,17,'','',5),(186,34,17,'','',6),(187,35,17,'','',7),(188,11,17,'','',8),(205,64,11,'','',2),(206,73,11,'','',3),(207,66,11,'','',4),(208,13,11,'','',5),(209,90,11,'','',6),(210,86,11,'','',7),(211,87,11,'','',8),(212,96,11,'','',9),(213,98,11,'','',10),(214,99,11,'','',11),(215,100,11,'','',12),(216,NULL,11,'','',13),(217,NULL,11,'','',14),(218,NULL,11,'','',15),(219,NULL,11,'','',16),(220,92,17,'','',9),(221,89,17,'','',10),(222,91,17,'','',11),(223,88,17,'','',12),(224,95,17,'','',13),(225,94,17,'','',14),(226,93,17,'','',15),(227,97,17,'','',16),(274,23,25,'<p>American patriotism was galvanized into action, if not established in the first place by the successive World Wars. &nbsp;Having love for one\'s country took a new meaning and US soldiers, particularly Navy men, prolonged their fraternal bonds with the military by getting tattoos.</p>','<p>Another soldier inspired by his commitment to his country.</p>',2),(275,149,25,'<p>Often tattoos in the military are simply a means by which to keep preoccupied. &nbsp;As action-packed as the task is sometimes, accounts from soldiers overseas have revealed the occasional boring nature of being a soldier. &nbsp;Tattoos are a way of glorifying a soldier\'s service while also giving him and his companions entertainment.</p>','<p>The prominent tattoo of a young American marine.</p>',3),(276,157,25,'<p>The POW (Prisoner of War) and MIA (Missing in Action) designs have great meaning to many war veterans. &nbsp;Many American soldiers were tagged with the POW acronym while at war in Europe during World War II (most frequently in Germany). &nbsp;In consequence, countless soldiers who have come after these veterans have inscribed the same phrase in solidarity with their brothers in war. &nbsp;</p>','<p>A homage to the brave American soldiers who were and are Prisoners of War.</p>',4),(277,156,25,'<p>World War II tattoos have become popular again in the 21st Century, representing homeage to those who came before us and fought for us. &nbsp;This generation has experienced terrorism and the War in Afghanistan first-hand which have contributed to a renewed sense of reverence to American veterans. &nbsp;&nbsp;</p>','<p>A vivid display of respect to the soliders who fought for America in World War II.</p>',5),(278,NULL,25,'','',6),(279,NULL,25,'','',7),(280,NULL,25,'','',8),(281,101,26,'<p>As women were granted more and more rights in the 1920\'s and 1930\'s, society accepted that they had every right to do what men did. &nbsp;When World War II came to a close and soldiers returned home--intent on getting tattoos--women got inspired. &nbsp;Women jumped at the opporunity to express themselves just as men could and the tattoo industry was opened up to twice as many people as before. &nbsp;The effect of this movement was enormous, considering the matriarchal position most American women were obliged to. &nbsp;As role models and an industry audience constituting half of the American population, once women started getting tattoos, much of the country was inspired to follow suit. &nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Furthermore, women typically did not want the same types of tattoos of men; tattoos became less of a symbol of power and masculinity and gained a softer edge. &nbsp;Tattoos depicting beautiful artistry or flowers or such gentle images were unheard of before the women\'s rights movement but gradually became commonplace. &nbsp;A paradigm shift occurred in America toward tattoos, and they began to symbolize traits such as elegance and beauty. &nbsp;This came as stark contrast to the primary utility of tattoos at the time, which was distinguishing the \"tough guys\". &nbsp;The women\'s rights movement transformed the industry to highlight a different side of the tattoo business. &nbsp;This change has had a lasting effect, as evidenced by the numerous \"feel-good\" designs on the current list of most common tattoos. &nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Finally, this new liberty for women opened the door for a new perspective from the average American family on tattoos. &nbsp;The younger generations were exposed to motherly figures with tattoos and getting one was no longer seen as such a harsh action. &nbsp;This also opened the door for tattoos to represent more than the fraternal bonds of the military. &nbsp;Religious tattoos, fictional figures, and a plethora of joyful expression were all inscribed with ink by tattooists, nd the business was able to expand even more. &nbsp;The women\'s rights movement allowed the industry to be exposed to not only a new demographic of people, but a new spectrum of inscriptions as well.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>','<p>Women admiring a tattoo in the World War II era.</p>',1),(322,113,30,'<p><span>\"Among Dai men tattoos are seen as a sign of strength and virility. Generally tattoos will be made in such a way as to accentuate and draw attention to their muscles. Although there are no fixed traditional designs among the Dai people, most commonly the tattoos will be of a ferocious beast such as a dragon or a tiger.\"</span></p>','',1),(282,14,14,'','<p>This lecture gives an overview of the Derung facial tattooing practices.&nbsp;</p>',10),(283,NULL,14,'','',11),(284,NULL,14,'','',12),(285,NULL,23,'','',9),(286,NULL,23,'','',10),(287,NULL,23,'','',11),(288,NULL,23,'','',12),(569,NULL,61,'','',9),(570,NULL,61,'','',10),(571,NULL,61,'','',11),(572,NULL,61,'','',12),(573,166,60,'<p>The findings of Otzi the iceman in September 1991 sparked an incredible amount of research about the history of tattoos and its purpose. &nbsp;On Otzi there was found several different locations on his body, primarily in his joints, with tattoos of straight lines in columns and rows as seen on the left. &nbsp;Early researchers believed that perhaps people who lived in the time circa 3500 BC thought that people would tattoo themselves in an effort to alleviate pain from their joints. &nbsp;It is such an incredible thing that we were able to discover such a specimen as Otzi, and for him to have markings that were preserved for as long as they were.</p>','',1),(564,174,61,'','',4),(565,NULL,61,'','',5),(566,NULL,61,'','',6),(567,NULL,61,'','',7),(568,NULL,61,'','',8),(562,19,61,'','',2),(563,158,61,'','',3),(627,55,66,'<p>This is a recount of Lars Krutak\'s trip to the first ever Tattoo Shop in Greece, which was first opened in 1977.</p>\r\n<p>\"<span>Jimmy&rsquo;s (at 13 Kyristou Street) is the oldest tattoo shop in Greece and was opened by Paul and Anna&rsquo;s father Jimmy in 1977. Jimmy is a legend in Greece, and back in the 50s and 60s he traveled the world as a seaman, picking up the tattooing bug in 1957 in Bombay. &ldquo;It was a hand-tapped job of a Native American chief and cost six rupees,&rdquo; he says. &ldquo;But damn if it didn&rsquo;t look good. I couldn&rsquo;t wait to get another!&rdquo; Jimmy later moved to Toronto and, during 1959-1965, skipped between Canada and New York City as a greenhorn tattooist. He came back to Athens in the late 60s and began tattooing out of his home in 1973. The studio opened four years later, despite that fact that tattooing was an illegal profession in Greece at that time. Jimmy persevered, however, and after five years of fighting city officials, &ldquo;Jimmy&rsquo;s&rdquo; was finally licensed in 1982 as the first tattoo studio to operate in Athens, not to mention Greece!\"</span></p>\r\n<p><span>Jimmy\'s tattoo shop is one of the first official ones in Europe and one of the most renound shops in all of Greece. &nbsp;It attracts quite the famous clientel ranging from&nbsp;<span>Greek models, soccer players, actors, doctors, attorneys, and sometimes, tourists.</span></span></p>','',1),(561,175,61,'<p>The Pacific islander cultures are not only well-known for their spiritual and meaningful tattoo designs, but also for the method of application. Although each country has their own unique designs, the traditional tools used in applying them are very similar among the overall region. In Samoa it\'s called the \"Au\", in New Zealand the \"uhi\" and in Tonga the \"tatatau\". They all shared the common design that resembles a small rake. It is made from&nbsp;<span>three parts: a comb, a shell plate, and a wooden handle. The small bone comb has very sharp teeth for puncturing the skin and inserting pigment. It is attached to a turtle shell plate, and both are tied with coconut fibre to a wooden handle. The teeth are covered with the natural-made dye and are gently tapped into the skin using a mallet.&nbsp;</span></p>','',1),(289,173,27,'<p>The methodology of tattooing was very different around the world at first. &nbsp;But as many different cultures and countries began going on voyages and settling elsewhere many places picked up on safer and more effective ways of preforming the art. &nbsp;The Europeans had the most advanced way that they were able to spread to places such as Oceania and to the Maori tribe in specific. &nbsp;The Europeans would use sharp metal tools to make the incisions and then ink compared to the Maori who used sharp bone and a combination of things as their ink.</p>','',1),(290,NULL,27,'','',2),(291,NULL,27,'','',3),(292,NULL,27,'','',4),(293,NULL,27,'','',5),(294,NULL,27,'','',6),(295,NULL,27,'','',7),(296,NULL,27,'','',8),(297,NULL,27,'','',9),(298,NULL,27,'','',10),(299,NULL,27,'','',11),(300,NULL,27,'','',12),(301,8,28,'<p>In this section I have chosen to focus on the two parts of Europe that contain the most rich background in anthropology, Greece and Albania, which tie into eachother. &nbsp;Much of what happened in Albania in the past, such as culturally signficant tattoos, has transformed and influenced everything that has happened recently all the way up to current day. &nbsp;The modern upstart of tattoos in Albania and Greece is what set fire to the spreading epidemic of tattoos all over Europe. &nbsp;And it wasn\'t just specific cultural tattoos that spread, as the use made its way accross Europe there became more and more obscure uses of body art.</p>','',1),(302,NULL,28,'','',2),(303,NULL,28,'','',3),(304,NULL,28,'','',4),(305,NULL,28,'','',5),(306,NULL,28,'','',6),(307,NULL,28,'','',7),(308,NULL,28,'','',8),(309,NULL,28,'','',9),(310,NULL,28,'','',10),(311,NULL,28,'','',11),(312,NULL,28,'','',12),(545,169,53,'<p><strong>Women as scared to the tribe:</strong></p>\r\n<p>Much of significance of the scars is centered around the religious beliefs of the tribe. As the bearer of children, the fertility of the land and of family lineage depends on the woman.</p>\r\n<p>When a girl enters the child bearing years, she becomes scared to the community, this transformation is represented by the scars that are added to the belly. With the navel as the axis, the elaborate designs are centered around where life will be formed. This scarification secures the girl into womanhood for the whole tribe to see.&nbsp;</p>','<p><a href=\"http://dh101.humanities.ucla.edu/DH101Fall12Lab5/items/show/169\" target=\"_self\">The Religious Significance of Women\'s Scarification</a></p>',2),(546,73,53,'<p><strong>Men:&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n<p>Similar to men, boys receive their scars as they age. Oftentimes, the act of scarification is a test of courage. As the ceremony of scarification involves the entire community, the strength the boys show as they are being scarred is important as a right of passage in the community. As they mature, the more scars a boy can endure is directly related to strength and how well they are respected in the community.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>The body art received in this processes is also very important in finding a mate. The stronger and more powerful the male appears and the more womanly and fertile the woman appears, the more attractive they are in finding a partner for life. This is very important as well in maintain tribal identity as the young men and women of a tribe are responsible for passing down the traditions &nbsp;to future generations.&nbsp;</p>','',3),(547,NULL,53,'','',4),(548,NULL,53,'','',5),(549,NULL,53,'','',6),(550,NULL,53,'','',7),(551,NULL,53,'','',8),(528,NULL,55,'','',5),(527,NULL,55,'','',4),(526,NULL,55,'','',3),(525,253,55,'<div class=\"column\">\r\n<p>This sort of regulation soon spread to the regions of the world including the United States. This document is an example of the regulations imposed on this form of body art prohibiting any branding or scarification done under and circumstance without a licensed professional. Under this regulation, scarification must be only performed in a medical facility.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Although these regulations led to a dissemination of scarification as a widespread practice in Africa, the practice still remains. The tribes that remain closer to their tribal identity and farther away from the national and regional government proceeded and continue to proceed with their body are practices. &nbsp;As it is a practice that is so centralized towards tribal identity, the tribes that see it as so important to their culture and ancestry continue on with scarification.&nbsp;</p>\r\n</div>','',2),(488,64,48,'<p>In the height of Trans-Atlantic slave trade, facial scarification saw a shift in purpose. The introduction of this slave trade played a dual role in changing the role of the scars meanwhile uniting the members of these tribes under their specific identification. In addition, scarification as a form of identification was taken in a new form as the facial cuts were given as both a form of protection and categorization:</p>\r\n<p><strong>Protection:</strong>&nbsp; In efforts to evade the slavery, the tribes began to use heavy facial scarring to make them appear less attractive to slave traders. It was thought that this type of scar would protect young children from harm.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>Categorization:  </strong>Facial cuts were given in hopes that it would make it easier to recognize relatives and lost children if the possibility of reclaiming them should happen. Based on the scars, relatives would know which tribe and even which family they belong to.</p>','',1),(524,7,55,'<p><strong>Regulation:</strong></p>\r\n<p>At the turn of the century&nbsp;major concerns with the brutality of scarification as well as the concerns with health lead to a movement or human rights, promoting the regulation of scarification. The Human Rights Movement in Africa led to an outlaw of this forbidding a practice that was once so central to a family, ethnic, and ancestral identity.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>New regulations included President Rawling of Ghana\'s 1989 formal declaration against FGM/FGC and other harmful traditional practices, abolishing any practice&nbsp;that is injurious to a person&rsquo;s health and well-being, as well as the 1990&nbsp;law against tribal marking due to children&rsquo;s rights in Nigeria.&nbsp;Although not widely enforcably, these laws led to a decrease in the presence of communities that remain well regulated by the local government.&nbsp;</p>','',1),(499,85,52,'<p>Scarring patterns, rituals, and purpose vary across the tribes of Africa. This&nbsp;body art communicates the elements of the cultural system and religious beliefs of the community.&nbsp;Each tribe identifies itself with its specific scars and ceremonies that are an integral part of their culture.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>The act of scarification brings both the tribe and the family together. As the painful ritual is something that only they share, the scars are viewed as signs of love and respect among the tribe. As the scars last for a lifetime, the markings cement their bond with the tribal identity.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Please view the video clip to the left for more on tribal identity.&nbsp;</p>','',1),(500,NULL,52,'','',2),(501,NULL,52,'','',3),(502,NULL,52,'','',4),(503,NULL,52,'','',5),(504,NULL,52,'','',6),(505,NULL,52,'','',7),(506,NULL,52,'','',8),(507,NULL,52,'','',9),(508,NULL,52,'','',10),(509,NULL,52,'','',11),(510,NULL,52,'','',12),(511,NULL,52,'','',13),(512,NULL,52,'','',14),(513,NULL,52,'','',15),(514,NULL,52,'','',16),(515,154,53,'<p><span><strong>Women:</strong><br /></span></p>\r\n<p><span>Traditionally, women\'s bodies are scarred to signify certain stages of life. The most commonly seen scars begin with the torso, scarring specific patterns at about the age of ten. When a girl reaches puberty, she recieves more under the breasts. After bearing her first child, a woman will recieve scars arms, back, and legs. </span></p>\r\n<p><span>Both patterns and purpose vary by tribe to tribe as each tribe has specific customs and ritual. For example, in some tribes by&nbsp;</span>the time women reach adulthood their bodies were covered with eight different patterns are not considered suitable to marry without these scars. Meanwhile in other the scarification is less intricate and less extensive.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>In this video clip provided by the Cantor Arts Center, artist Magdalene Odundo discusses body adornment and scarification as a part of her culture and as an inspiration in her work.</p>','<p>Click this still image to view this video clip</p>',1),(529,NULL,55,'','',6),(530,NULL,55,'','',7),(531,NULL,55,'','',8),(605,177,64,'<div class=\"WordSection1\">\r\n<p>Around the 7th to the 10th Century is the time that the Pict tribe was thriving in Scotland before they were wiped out and colonized by the Romans. &nbsp;Because of the lack of information known about this group of people it isn&rsquo;t completely known the method of practice that this group used. &nbsp;The information that researchers have collected has suggested that they were a pretty colorful group of people, because of that it has lead to hypotheses that suggest it was simply body paint and that they would reapply it constantly. &nbsp;Other hypotheses suggest that there isn&rsquo;t enough information to claim that these people were even tattooed at all. &nbsp;The topic of Picts and tattoos has a high level of controversy.&nbsp;</p>\r\n</div>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>','',2),(620,6,48,'<p>In Lauren Culivan\'s piece,&nbsp;<a href=\"http://dh101.humanities.ucla.edu/DH101Fall12Lab5/items/show/6\" target=\"_self\">The Meanings Behind the Marks: Scarification and the People of Wa</a>, slave trade or rather slave raiding is responsible for the continuation and dominance of this practices throughout the tribes of Africa. \"Tribal markings became highly important not only for ethnic identification but because they allowed one to retain their roots even if they were captured and taken into slavery.&nbsp;Once taken into bondage, tribal marks allowed slaves to unite with other members of their ethnic group who had been captured.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>It seems that as a result of slave raiders consistently threatening a community&rsquo;s solidarity, unity, and security, Northerners became more conscious of their identity and developed a great pride in their ethnic heritage and community.14 Through the practice of tribal markings, Northerners showed that they were not only conscious of their identity but more concerned in keeping their identity.\"</p>','',2),(323,28,30,'<p><span>\"The Dai people of China have an ancient tattooing tradition. Both men and women among the Dai are tattooed.\"</span></p>','',2),(324,41,30,'<p>This website provides a general overview of the tattooing practices in China, while going into specific detail on the Dai tribe\'s tattoo culture.&nbsp;</p>','',3),(325,NULL,30,'','',4),(326,NULL,30,'','',5),(327,NULL,30,'','',6),(328,NULL,30,'','',7),(329,NULL,30,'','',8),(448,125,43,'<p>The importance of tattoos in Tonga (called tatatau), are similar to that of the Samoans. When the first Dutch explorers made it to Tonga, they took note of native men with black paint on their waists and legs. Through usage of the same tools and many shared traditions, Tongan tatatau\'s are applied through the typical polynesian method. Historically, chiefs and other high ranks often had large and complex tattoos to display their heritage, however over the last 200 years the art of the Tongan tatatau has diminished completely. Through the intense Christianization of Tonga, the art was shunned and seen as a form of mutilation. Once one of the most prominent traditions, original Tongan tatatau is now dead. There is a small group of Tongan tattoo artists trying to revive the art, however, it certainly has lost a lot of meaning over the 200 year death. The Tongans look to Samoa to try and understand their own lost traditions, with many similarities being found between the two countries. The customs of the countries certainly overlap, but the Tongans will continue to fight to find their own tatatau identity.</p>','',1),(449,121,43,'','',2),(450,184,43,'','',3),(451,165,43,'','',4),(452,NULL,43,'','',5),(361,NULL,33,'','',16),(360,NULL,33,'','',15),(359,NULL,33,'','',14),(358,NULL,33,'','',13),(357,NULL,33,'','',12),(356,NULL,33,'','',11),(355,NULL,33,'','',10),(354,NULL,33,'','',9),(353,191,33,'','',8),(352,17,33,'','',7),(351,18,33,'','',6),(350,192,33,'','',5),(349,20,33,'','',4),(348,21,33,'','',3),(347,25,33,'','',2),(346,189,33,'<p>Like many other polynesian cultures, the Maori community was highly tribalized. From the beginning, the facial moko was used to differentiate the classes and establish the high ranks. The methods of application remain similar between the polynesian, however because of the location of moko tattoos, the Maori process was much more dangerous. As the chisel was tapped into the skin, it sometimes cut so deep it could actually puncture holes through the cheek or nostril. It remains a mystery how the details of Maori tattoos existed despite the destruction of facial skin. Some believe that it was the pigments they used, while the Maori may believe it to be the gods taking care of the healing process.</p>\r\n<p>Despite the settlement of the British in New Zealand, the art of Maori tattooing has suffered little. It did take many attacks from the missionaries who claimed that it was mutilation, however the pride of the Maori overtook the new ideals. Although it is less common for Maori\'s to go through the entire traditional process, moko tattoos are far from dead. In modern day New Zealand, there is nothing that makes the statement &ldquo;I am Maori&rdquo; more clearly than a full-face moko.</p>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>','',1),(362,29,31,'<p><span>\"At the beginning of the Meiji period the Japanese government, wanting to protect its image and make a good impression on the West, outlawed tattoos, and irezumi took on connotations of criminality. Nevertheless, fascinated foreigners went to Japan seeking the skills of tattoo artists, and traditional tattooing continued underground.</span><br /><br /><span>Tattooing was legalized by the occupation forces in 1945, but has retained its image of criminality. For many years, traditional Japanese tattoos were associated with the yakuza, Japan&rsquo;s notorious mafia, and many businesses in Japan (such as public baths, fitness centers and hot springs) still ban customers with tattoos.</span><br /><br /><span>Tattooing and other forms of body decoration and body modification, as in much of the western world, are gaining in popularity in Japan. However, Japanese young people who choose to get tattooed are most often choosing &ldquo;one point&rdquo; designs &mdash; small designs that can be completed in one sitting &mdash; usually in the American or tribal styles. More recently, however sanskrit Siddham script tattoos are becoming more and more fashionable.</span><br /><br /><span>Traditional irezumi is still done by specialist tattooists, but it is painful, time-consuming and expensive: a typical traditional body suit tattoo (covering the arms, back, upper legs and chest, but leaving an untattooed space down the center of the body) can take one to five years of weekly visits to complete and cost in excess of US$30,000.\"</span></p>','',1),(363,32,31,'<p><span>A man receiving a traditional irezumi Japanese tattoo in a back alley private tattoo parlor in Tokyo.</span></p>','',2),(364,31,31,'<p><span>Photograph of a man with a traditionally designed Japanese Irezumi tattoo covering his back.</span></p>\r\n<div><span style=\"color: #333333; font-family: \'Lucida Grande\', Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 12px; line-height: 18px; text-align: left;\"><br /></span></div>','',3),(365,119,31,'<p><span>This webpage provides much of the background information about when and why tattoos were popular in Japan.</span></p>','',4),(366,27,31,'<p><span>\"The earliest evidence of tattooing in Japan is found in clay figurines with&nbsp;</span><span>painted or engraved</span><span>&nbsp;faces representing tattoos. The oldest of these clay figurines have been recovered from tombs dated to 3,000 BCE or indeed before this time. Numerous other such figurines have been found in various tombs dating from the 2nd and 3rd millennia BCE. These figurines served as &lsquo;stand-ins&rsquo; or substitutes for living individuals who symbolically accompanied the dead on their journey into the afterlife. It is commonly held that these tattooed marking held strong spiritual significance. The very first written record of the Japanese practicing the art of tattooing is found within a Chinese dynastic history compiled around 297 CE. The Japanese were interested in he art mostly for aesthetic or decorative uses &ndash; in contrast to their earlier spiritual significance.<span>&nbsp;The</span><span>&nbsp;Horis</span><span>&nbsp;&ndash; the Japanese tattoo masters &ndash; were the undisputed experts of tattooing in their time. Their use of colors, perspective and imaginative designs moved the practice in a completely different direction.</span>&nbsp;The classic Japanese tattoo is a full body suit.\"</span></p>','',5),(367,42,31,'<p><span>\"Archeologists have found the Japanese tattoo art in many clay figurines from ancient tombs that dated back to 3000 BC or more. These clay figurines have human faces with tattoo marks engraved on them. It is believed that these figurines were either living individuals or statues whose purpose was to accompany the dead into the after life journey. These tattoos were considered to be religious and were known to possess magical powers. Even the history of Chinese dynasty in 297 AD states that Japan consisted of The Horis, which were the masters of tattoo art.\"</span></p>','',6),(368,45,31,'<p><span>\"This paper is a holistic look at the world of tattoo. It covers the history of the practice in three major world regions, Europe, Asia and the Pacific, from the earliest known references to tattooing to modern day tattoo culture that spans the globe. It also provides a discussion of some of the major issues that surround the practice, including such topics as tattooing in relation to the body, authenticity, commodification and meaning, functions, medical and legal concerns and the impact of technological developments on the practice, and the increase in popularity of tattooing in recent decades.\"</span></p>','',7),(369,46,31,'<p>\"Tattooing for spiritual and decorative purposes in Japan is thought to extend back to at least the Jomon or paleolithic period (approximately 10,000 BCE) and was widespread during various periods for both the Japanese and the native&nbsp;<a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ainu_people\">Ainu.</a>&nbsp;Chinese visitors observed and remarked on the tattoos in Japan (300 BCE).</p>\r\n<p>In Japanese the word used for traditional designs or those that are applied using traditional methods is irezumi (\"insertion of ink\"), while \"tattoo\" is used for non-Japanese designs. The earliest evidence of tattooing in Japan comes from figurines called dogu. Most of these date to 3000 years ago and display similar markings to the tattooed mouths found among the women of the Ainu (the Indigenous people of Japan).</p>\r\n<p>Tattoo enthusiasts may refer to tattoos as tats, ink, art or work, and to tattooists as artists. The latter usage is gaining support, with mainstream art galleries holding exhibitions of tattoo designs and photographs of tattoos. Tattoo designs that are mass-produced and sold to tattoo artists and studios and displayed in shop are known as flash.\"</p>','',8),(604,176,64,'<p>Unlike the forms of tattooing today in Europe, the first known tattooing method was the one that Otzi used 5300 years ago. &nbsp;After carefully researching the body and what was underneath his skin, it was determined that he made very fine incisions most likely with sharpened rock and then used some quantity of soot and charcoal as the ink for the tattoo. &nbsp;These tattoos were found on many joints and thought to be a method of pre-historic acupuncture. &nbsp;It is interesting to think about this because the first evidence of any practice of acupuncture wasn&rsquo;t until 2000 years later in China. &nbsp;There is thought to be no link between Otzi and the original practice of acupuncture in China. &nbsp;This discovery was made after many people had assumed that the Europeans took up the method and practice from the Polynesians after a few voyages.</p>','',1),(398,47,36,'<div id=\"dublin-core-description\" class=\"element\">\r\n<div class=\"element-text\">\"It appears that tattooing in Asia is as ancient a practice as it is in the rest of the world. While we have no Asian equivalent to the tattooed Iceman, prehistoric figurines have been found that show distinct markings on their skin that are thought to represent tattoos.<br />As in other cultures, markings on the &ldquo;skin&rdquo; of the figurines are thought to be representations of fertility. It seems common world-wide for women (or statues of women) to be marked on belly, breasts and pubic area.<br />We have written records from Asia that are very ancient and as early as 3oo BCE there are mentions of tattoos and their symbolic meanings. It is clear that in Asia, as in other parts of the world, tattoos were not just for decoration but for punishment&ndash;criminals were often permanently marked.\"</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n</div>\r\n<div id=\"dublin-core-creator\" class=\"element\">&nbsp;</div>','',1),(399,45,36,'<p>\"This paper is a holistic look at the world of tattoo. It covers the history of the practice in three major world regions, Europe, Asia and the Pacific, from the earliest known references to tattooing to modern day tattoo culture that spans the globe. It also provides a discussion of some of the major issues that surround the practice, including such topics as tattooing in relation to the body, authenticity, commodification and meaning, functions, medical and legal concerns and the impact of technological developments on the practice, and the increase in popularity of tattooing in recent decades.\"</p>','',2),(400,46,36,'<p><span>\"Tattooing is one of the oldest art forms on the planet, dating to prehistoric times and cave dwellers who often created tattoos as part of ritual practices linked to shamanism, protection, connection with their gods, and embuing them with magica powers. Early tattooing was used to symbolize the fertility of the earth and of womankind, preservation of life after death, the sacredness of chieftainship and other cultural factors.\"</span></p>','',3),(401,NULL,36,'','',4),(402,NULL,36,'','',5),(403,NULL,36,'','',6),(404,NULL,36,'','',7),(405,NULL,36,'','',8),(407,258,38,'<p>As much as tattooing today is associated with American culture, it originated in Pacific Island cultures such as Tahiti, Maori, and Samoa. &nbsp;The first records of North American tattooing begin with voyages to the Pacific Islands in the 17th and 18th Centuries. &nbsp;English sailors returned from their excursions with both Polynesian tattoos and tattooed Polynesians. &nbsp;They adopted the carving techniques of the Pacific Islanders and added their own influence with their superior technologies. &nbsp;Though at first seen as marks of savagery, tattoos transitioned to a mark of adventure as sailors continued to get them. &nbsp;This transition was complete in the Americas with eager tattoo artists\' creativity and enthusiasm. &nbsp;From the Polynesian Islands to the British Royal Navy to European colonialism into the Americas, the art form slowly diffused around the world and has flourished in North America. &nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><span>Martin Hildebrandt was the first tattoo artist in the United States and set up shop in New York City in 1846. &nbsp;His primary audience at first was sailors, as well as soldiers fighting in the Civil War. &nbsp;All of his work was done by hand, as the Pacific Island cultures before him had done. &nbsp;In 1891 Samuel O\'Reilly patented the first electric tattoo machine which transformed the industry. &nbsp;Through the early 20th Century tattoos were administered primarily to servicemen and sailors. &nbsp;Tattooists were typically from the working class and seldom did they have artistic training. &nbsp;Though tattooists were usually not good artists when the business was developing in America, it is important to note several artists whose influence is still being felt today such as Sailor Jerry, Charlie Wagner, Cap Coleman, and Paul Rogers.</span></p>\r\n<p><span>The early tattoo parlors were located in hidden alleys, next to arcades and barber shops, and in other less than glamorous places. &nbsp;They provided a home away from home for many sailors, war veterans, drunks, and even young boys who took apprenticeship under an established tattooist. &nbsp;However, these \"homes\" were radically changed in the 1960\'s when the government shook the industry. &nbsp;Charlie Wagner was fined by New York City for using unsterile needles, and an outbreak of Hepatitis B caused many areas to ban tattooing altogether. &nbsp;This time period saw few people other than prison inmates, bikers, and soldiers to get tattoos, cementing the practice\'s association with the socially marginal.</span></p>\r\n<p><span>&nbsp;</span></p>','<p>Tattoo legend Sailor Jerry</p>',1),(408,259,38,'','<p>Charlie Wagner at work in his studio</p>',2),(409,260,38,'','<p>American pioneer in the early tattoo industry Cap Coleman</p>',3),(410,261,38,'','<p>Paul Rogers and his art-filled sleeves</p>',4),(411,NULL,38,'','',5),(412,NULL,38,'','',6),(413,NULL,38,'','',7),(414,NULL,38,'','',8),(415,263,39,'<p>Just as the Western world has molded and revolutionized the world in terms of technology, economy, military skill, and more; so too did the West change the perspective of the world on body art. &nbsp;The practice of tattooing today is no longer savagery, nor is it for only the European aristocracy; it is a practice that just about one quarter of young adults in America engages in. &nbsp;America has transformed the industry into what it is today: by encouraging women to obtain tattoos, by promoting individuality, and by fostering the fraternal bonds of war. &nbsp;North America is at the cutting edge of new technologies and cultural advancements today in many fields, and the tattoo business is no exception. &nbsp;Peace tattoos, dragon tattoos, religious tattoos--all originated in the Americas. &nbsp;Even though the first tattoos didn\'t come from America, it is safe to say that America is the birthplace of the modern tattoo and the home of the industry from the late 19th Century until today.</p>','<p>A new tattoo machine that is more precise, sterile, user-friendly, elegant, and practical than the original models.</p>',1),(416,136,40,'<p><span>The way body art is perceived is largely dictated by the media\'s outlook on the topic which has been extremely variable even over the past 30 years. &nbsp;Media discourse has silently controlled the industry, dictating the social implications of Western tattoos for decades. &nbsp;Mainstream press exercises incredible control over almost every cultural aspect of our modern world and body art is certainly no exception. &nbsp;</span></p>\r\n<p><span>Typical media accounts since the 1980\'s offer a distinction between tattoos of bikers, sailor, and convicts with those of educated professionals. &nbsp;This contrast became so bold that it essentially split all tattoos, tattoo artists, and tattoo-getters into one of the two categories. &nbsp;While this discourse is still present today, it does in a very subdued form--one that hardly compares to the contrast in the late 20th Century. &nbsp;What finally broke the stereotype as well as the separation between these two groups is the prominence of media. &nbsp;The tattoos that were portrayed in magazines, news articles, interviews, and more were typically those of educated professionals. &nbsp;This propelled the belief that tattoos had evolved from mere militant symbolism or tokens of rebellion. &nbsp;The media conveyed that tattoos are meaningful and even admirable, advocating one\'s beliefs. &nbsp;Particularly to the middle class tattoos became more accessible and desirable. &nbsp;Even advertisements shifted to illustrate more professionalism in the tattoo industry. &nbsp;In specific, major tattoo magazines such as<span class=\"apple-converted-space\">&nbsp;</span><em>ITA</em><span class=\"apple-converted-space\">&nbsp;</span>and<span class=\"apple-converted-space\">&nbsp;</span><em>Tattoo Advocate</em>&nbsp;publicly refused to accept advertisements from tattoo suppliers (who are typically representative of the biker group).</span></p>\r\n<p><span>A major unforeseen effect media has had on the tattoo industry is the shift in its target audience. &nbsp;Though the primary recipients of tattoos began in America as war veterans, \"tough\" bikers, the homeless, and other members of the lower class, it quickly was shifted to the middle class with the inception of social media and the instantaneous dissemination of information. &nbsp;Specifically concerning tattooists who were worried about their reputation, the tattoo industry clientele rapidly shifted to the middle-class. &nbsp;A tattoo hierarchy has been created as opposed to the previous single entity of an audience. &nbsp;For instance, prison tattooists are far less prestigious than a mentored tattooist in an urban area in the tattoo community. &nbsp;Tattoos at parties, tattoos to express spiritual beliefs, tattoos to display beauty, and other motivations and representations stemming from the middle class have all become popular. &nbsp;While the upper class (excluding modern athletes) has generally always been consistent in being above or \"too professional\" for tattoos, the middle class adopted the art form as its own as new media emerged. &nbsp;Furthermore, recent technologies have been able to assure the safe nature of tattooing, winning favor with the middle class.</span></p>\r\n<p><span>Media has driven the resurgence of the tattoo industry and continues to push it to new heights. &nbsp;With the contemporary liberal movement of individuality and the outward expression of one\'s beliefs, it is safe to assume that the industry will continue to grow for years to come. &nbsp;Media has broadcast the practice in a light very different from that in years past, while simultaneously advocating its safety and introducing a new paradigm to its relationship with professionalism.</span></p>','<p>Johnny Depp and other modern pop stars provide role models for the younger generations. &nbsp;Tattoos such as these promote the industry for millions of young Americans.</p>',1),(417,137,40,'','<p>Tattoos magazines such as&nbsp;<em>Tattoo</em> Spirit, have contributed greatly to the recent rise in popularity of the tattoo industry.</p>',2),(418,138,40,'','<p>Media has affected the tattoo industry so much that it has even become an inspiration for some; specifically those who are very adamant about their search providers.</p>',3),(419,139,40,'','<p>Chris \"Birdman\" Anderson and other athletes have utilized the practice of tattoos to convey to the world their favorite symbols, belifes, and artwork. &nbsp;The result is a skin surface which resembles an art canvas.</p>',4),(420,NULL,40,'','',5),(421,NULL,40,'','',6),(422,NULL,40,'','',7),(423,NULL,40,'','',8),(424,NULL,40,'','',9),(425,NULL,40,'','',10),(426,NULL,40,'','',11),(427,NULL,40,'','',12),(428,143,41,'<p><strong>Tattoo Popularity Today</strong></p>\r\n<p>The current trends of today have a huge social impact on how others see tattoos and what tattoos others are inspired to get. &nbsp;These trends in popularity of specific tattoos and genres of tattoos have been very variable over the years. &nbsp;According to a survey from USA Today, 24% of Americans between the ages of 18 and 50 are tattooed. &nbsp;In comparison, surveys from 2003 suggest that only about 15% of that population had tattoos, a shocking jump. &nbsp;That number rises again to 36% when only considering Americans aged between 18 and 29 years old. &nbsp;The survey showed that nearly 70% of those tattooed did so before they were 24 years old. &nbsp;These numbers are astounding and imply that the numbers will only continue to rise. &nbsp;Soon it may be considered uncommon to not have a tattoo, which is a scary thought considering the contrast in the demographic and popularity of tattoos only 30 or 40 years ago. &nbsp;As more and more young people are getting tattoos and the body is becoming perceived more and more as a canvas for individual expression, it\'s hard to imagine the popularity of tattoos in America not continue to trend.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Trending Designs</strong></p>\r\n<p>The most common tattoo design in America today is the tribal tattoo, in many cases related to Maori or Polynesian ties. &nbsp;Following tribal designs is the design of the star as a tattoo. &nbsp;Angel and cross designs come in third and fourth, representing the expression of religious affiliation. &nbsp;Sometimes also used as a memorial symbol. The angel tattoo is a less subtle declaration of faith than the simple cross, which is the most recognized symbol of Christianity. &nbsp;Dragons, butterflies, fairies, and other \"feel-good\" images round out the list of most common tattoo designs. &nbsp;This list indicates that the primary driving force behind tattoos is still heritage and family ties, though religion is becoming more and more of an inspiration. &nbsp;People are also galvanized to get tattoos that permanently remind them of happiness and joyful sentiments.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Trending Cities</strong></p>\r\n<p>According to an NBC News survey, the most tattooed city in America is Miami, Florida. &nbsp;Averaging over 24 tattoo shops for every 100,000 people, it\'s no wonder why the television series&nbsp;<em>Miami Ink</em>&nbsp;has become so popular. &nbsp;The NBC survey shows that the most tattooed cities in America (based off of tattoo shops per capita, according to the US Census) are very similar to the list of most populated cities in America. &nbsp;The more urban the area, the more common tattoos seem to be, per person. &nbsp;This can partially be attributed to social conformity and the tendencies of groups to act in similar ways. &nbsp;For instance, drug or biker gangs heavily populate many urban areas and often have a high percentage of members with tattoos. &nbsp;</p>','<p>The most popular tattoo design in America today: the tribal tattoo.</p>',1),(429,144,41,'','<p>The Nautical Star is the second most popular tattoo design in America today.</p>',2),(430,145,41,'','<p>The cross tattoo is the most fundamental visual representation of one\'s faith.</p>',3),(431,146,41,'','<p>Dragon tattoos and other fictional symbols are often intended to convey character traits such as strength or courage.</p>',4),(432,147,41,'','<p>Flower tattoos have become especially popular among the growing population of females with tattoos.</p>',5),(433,NULL,41,'','',6),(434,NULL,41,'','',7),(435,NULL,41,'','',8),(436,NULL,41,'','',9),(437,NULL,41,'','',10),(438,NULL,41,'','',11),(439,NULL,41,'','',12),(440,148,42,'<p><span>Tattoos have long carried with them the stigma of a rebellious or individualistic spirit. &nbsp;From the harsh war veterans to the hard-nosed biker gangs, tattoos became popular on \"tough\" guys in America and have had a parallel connotation ever since. &nbsp;Tattoos are often associated with \"tough guys\", drug-users, alcoholics, and other social groups that society tends to scorn. &nbsp;Though new media and a boom in popularity are working to eradicate these stereotypes, they certainly are still in existence today. &nbsp;Studies have shown a correlation between number of tattoos and other negative variables which help to prove these stereotypes. &nbsp;For example, studies show that more tattoos typically mean more arrests for reasons other than traffic violations. &nbsp;Moreover, a greater quantity of tattoos is also related to increased monthly marijuana use and number of sexual partners a person has had in the past year. &nbsp;While the industry is evolving to quell these stereotypes, it is no wonder some parents and young adults alike are so opposed to the idea of tattoos.&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n<p><span>One way in which this stigma is being nullified is by converting the perception of the tattoo. &nbsp;As opposed to the \"tough guy\" vibe, today\'s liberal society is encouraging a more \"hip\" and individualistic approach to tattoos. &nbsp;Whether it is \"the thing to do\" among young people is yet to be seen, but steps are definitely being taken in that direction. &nbsp;This is evidenced by the increased number of tattoos conveying religious beliefs, jubilant expressions, and upbeat symbols. &nbsp;</span></p>\r\n<p><span>The converse side of tattoos conveying a sense of being different or hip is that they do not always express professionalism. &nbsp;Many professional jobs, especially in the business world, are still quite dubious as to the social expression of tattoos. &nbsp;A percentage of these professional employers refuse to hire prospective employees who have tattoos, and a greater percentage insist that tattoos must be concealed on working employees at all times. &nbsp;The stigmas of tattoos are still very prevalent in our society and tattoos are considered by many to not be conducive to establishing trust between an employer and prospective employee. &nbsp;This concept of the effect of tattoos on professionalism and their social implications is further elucidated by the video on the right.</span></p>','<p>A CNN documentary elucidating the social implications of tattoos in America today.</p>',1),(441,NULL,42,'','',2),(442,NULL,42,'','',3),(443,NULL,42,'','',4),(444,NULL,42,'','',5),(445,NULL,42,'','',6),(446,NULL,42,'','',7),(447,NULL,42,'','',8),(453,NULL,43,'','',6),(454,NULL,43,'','',7),(455,NULL,43,'','',8),(456,NULL,43,'','',9),(457,NULL,43,'','',10),(458,NULL,43,'','',11),(459,NULL,43,'','',12),(460,NULL,43,'','',13),(461,NULL,43,'','',14),(462,NULL,43,'','',15),(463,NULL,43,'','',16),(559,NULL,59,'','',8),(560,NULL,59,'','',9),(557,NULL,59,'','',6),(558,NULL,59,'','',7),(464,67,44,'<p>The images above show the various types of tools used in this form of body modification. Traditionally, scarmasters use a Y-shaped tool that is made of iron.&nbsp;These tools are passed down from generations to generation, increasing the significance in terms of relationship to ancestors and tribal cultures. In addition, scarmasters often remain in one family. When a child reaches a certain age, the scarmaster will begin to teach them how to handle the tools, passing the job down to the next generation.&nbsp;</p>','',1),(465,199,44,'','',2),(466,NULL,44,'','',3),(467,NULL,44,'','',4),(468,NULL,44,'','',5),(469,NULL,44,'','',6),(470,NULL,44,'','',7),(471,NULL,44,'','',8),(472,NULL,44,'','',9),(473,NULL,44,'','',10),(474,NULL,44,'','',11),(475,NULL,44,'','',12),(476,87,45,'<p>The following summary is provided tattoo anthropologist&nbsp;<strong>Lars Krutak, </strong>in his article<strong> </strong><a href=\"http://dh101.humanities.ucla.edu/DH101Fall12Lab5/items/show/65\"><em>Scarification and Tattooing in Benin: The&nbsp;</em><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\"><em>B&eacute;tamarrib&eacute; Tribe of the Atakora Mountains</em><br /></span></a></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"text-align: left;\"><strong>Divination Ceremony:</strong> Before the cutting begins, the scarmaster divines which pattern will be cut into the face by casting a set of five cowrie shells into a ceramic pot filled with water.&nbsp;</span><span style=\"text-align: left;\">Depending on how the cowries land (face up or down) tells the scarist which pattern should be cut into the skin. Typically three or four major patterns with variations are follow, but this depends on the artist&rsquo;s repertoire and mastery of specific designs. Sometimes a piece of charcoal is also placed in the divining pot for purification.&nbsp;It is said that the spirit of the child controls the way the shells will fall.&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"text-align: left;\">The following descriptions correspond with the photo to the left:<br /><br />A) Once the divination ceremony has been completed, a bed of broad leafed plants is placed on the ground where the children will be cut.&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"text-align: left;\">B) Armed with what looks like an oversized iron arrowhead, the scarmaster, who often learns the art from the generation above, starts incisions on the temples. These designs resemble a horizontal series of V&rsquo;s</span><em style=\"text-align: left;\">&nbsp;</em><span style=\"text-align: left;\">that lead to the corner of the eyes. Above and below these marks, two or more long perpendicular lines named&nbsp;are cut that run down the cheek.&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"text-align: left;\">c) Next, the nasal regions and upper lips are marked with parallel vertical lines.&nbsp;</span><span style=\"text-align: left;\">Lastly, the forehead is scarred with three or four large V&rsquo;s that zigzag from one side to the other. The visual effect that results is a pattern so delicate that it is only visible in proper light.<br /></span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"text-align: left;\">D) Once the cutting is over, the child&rsquo;s facial orifices are thoroughly cleaned and cleared with another pot of water. The scarmaster utters a prayer to the spirits of the ancestors and says: &ldquo;Oh, our ancestors&hellip;today I present to you the child to whom the incisions have been made &ndash; please, take it under your protection and let it be in good health.&rdquo;&nbsp;</span><span style=\"text-align: left;\">Shea butter, which is used as an anti-inflammatory across West Africa, is then applied to the wounds with a chicken feather, and the baby is taken in the arms of its mother or grandmother to dry its wounds in the sun.&nbsp;</span><span style=\"text-align: left;\">In a final ritual action, the scarmaster spits charcoal on the cuts &ldquo;to keep away evil spirits&rdquo; and promote healing. Shea butter possesses a similar magic, and the B&eacute;tamarrib&eacute; say that it will repel any spirits of the underworld&nbsp;that might have been attracted by the flowing blood.</span></p>','',1),(477,98,45,'<ul>\r\n<li>Armed with what looks like an oversized iron arrowhead, the scarmaster, who often learns the art from the generation above, starts incisions on the temples. These designs resemble a horizontal series of V&rsquo;s<em>&nbsp;</em>that lead to the corner of the eyes. Above and below these marks, two or more long perpendicular lines named&nbsp;are cut that run down the cheek.</li>\r\n<li>Next, the nasal regions and upper lips are marked with parallel vertical lines.&nbsp;</li>\r\n<li>Lastly, the forehead is scarred with three or four large V&rsquo;s that zigzag from one side to the other. The visual effect that results is a pattern so delicate that it is only visible in proper light.</li>\r\n</ul>','',2),(478,NULL,45,'<ul>\r\n<li>Once the cutting is over, the child&rsquo;s facial orifices are thoroughly cleaned and cleared with another pot of water. The scarmaster utters a prayer to the spirits of the ancestors and says: &ldquo;Oh, our ancestors&hellip;today I present to you the child to whom the incisions have been made &ndash; please, take it under your protection and let it be in good health.&rdquo;</li>\r\n<li>Shea butter, which is used as an anti-inflammatory across West Africa, is then applied to the wounds with a chicken feather, and the baby is taken in the arms of its mother or grandmother to dry its wounds in the sun.&nbsp;</li>\r\n<li>In a final ritual action, the scarmaster spits charcoal on the cuts &ldquo;to keep away evil spirits&rdquo; and promote healing. Shea butter possesses a similar magic, and the B&eacute;tamarrib&eacute; say that it will repel any spirits of the underworld&nbsp;that might have been attracted by the flowing blood.</li>\r\n</ul>','',3),(479,65,45,'<p>For the full article decribing this ritual, __________</p>','',4),(480,NULL,45,'','',5),(481,NULL,45,'','',6),(482,NULL,45,'','',7),(483,NULL,45,'','',8),(484,NULL,45,'','',9),(485,NULL,45,'','',10),(486,NULL,45,'','',11),(487,NULL,45,'','',12),(553,187,59,'','',2),(554,NULL,59,'','',3),(555,188,59,'','',4),(556,NULL,59,'','',5),(552,185,59,'<p>Modern scarification procedures are typically performed in a far more sterile environment than the tribes of Africa. Most scarification takes place in body art shops, often tattoo shops, using sterilized surgical tools. This painful and expensive process is prolonged after the initial scarring as it is&nbsp;encouraged to irritate the incisions to create richer scars by applying peroxide and/or petroleum jelly. Once the scars begin to heal, the scab must be gently peeled away to prolong the healing process and create deeper, more prominent scars.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>With the popularization of scarification as come many medical concerns and dangers. The entire process of scarification cause trauma to the body and the scar is what appeals as a result of the healing process. Because it is not as common to find body shops that are willing to scar, the issue of self scarification (or do it yourself scars) brings a whole new danger. With, as with any cutting there is a risk of infection and extensive bleeding.&nbsp;</p>','',1),(574,61,60,'<p><span>\"The 57 tattoos sported by Otzi, the 5300 year old Tyrolean Iceman</span>&nbsp;<span>mummy, were made from fireplace soot that contained glittering, colorful precious stone crystals. &nbsp;<span>The determination supports prior research that the tattoos were associated with acupuncture treatments for chronic ailments suffered by the iceman, whose frozen body was found remarkably well preserved in the Similaun Glacier of the Alps in 1991.\"</span></span></p>','',2),(575,167,60,'<div class=\"textbox\">\r\n<div class=\"box_border clear\">\r\n<div class=\"text_margin\">\r\n<p>On a sunny day two hikers, Erika and Helmut Simon, from Nuremberg in Germany, were walking in the &Ouml;tztal Alps. Descending from the Final peak, the Simons thought it was a good idea to take a shortcut and left the marked footpath. As they walked past an area that was filled with an excess amount of meltwater, they saw something strange jutting out of the water. At first glance it looked as if it wasn\'t of any importance, but as they approached closer they realized that it was the body of a preserved human being.</p>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n<div class=\"box_container clear\">\r\n<div class=\"content_left\">They were only able to see the back, bare shoulders, and back of the head. The body layed with its face buried and chest pressed up against a flat rock.&nbsp;Before leaving the scene, they took a photograph of what they thought to be the unfortunate victim of a mountaineering accident a few years back.</div>\r\n<div class=\"content_right\">\r\n<p>Little did these two hikers know, they had just found an artifact that would stir up the world of tattoo history.</p>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>','',3),(576,111,60,'<p>\"The Tyrolean iceman, a 5300-year-old mummy, presents tattoos on different parts of his body. Skin samples of several line tattoos and a cross tattoo were investigated by optical microscopy and various electron microscopy techniques (TEM, EFETEM, EELS, EDXS, electron diffraction). The epidermis of the investigated skin areas was mostly lacking. The tattooing particles are distributed in the connective tissue and could be identified as soot. In some areas between the soot particles, different silicate crystals are present such as almandine and quartz, along with some not exactly definable crystals. The crystals possibly derived from stones of the fireplace from which the soot was taken for tattooing.\"</p>','',4),(577,60,60,'<p>\"<span>Otzi had several tattoos on his body, including a cross on the inside of his left knee; six parallel straight lines arranged in two rows on his back above his kidneys, each about 6 inches long; and several parallel lines on his ankles. Some have argued that tattooing may have been some sort of acupuncture.\"</span></p>','',5),(578,NULL,60,'','',6),(579,NULL,60,'','',7),(580,NULL,60,'','',8),(581,171,63,'<p>The process of tattooing in the Pacific Island cultures remains to be a very sacred art. True polynesian tattoo artists ensure that all proper traditions are observed and many of them use the tools that are now extremely outdated. The design process of a tattoo can take months or even years because every line, symbol and pattern has a meaning. A prayer is generally read before the tattoo process begins and then tap by tap, the ink is slowly and painfully embedded into the skin. Through the following videos, images and websites, the entire process of polynesian tattooing can be learned and the physical tattooing process can be watched.</p>','',1),(582,170,63,'','',2),(583,168,63,'','',3),(584,163,63,'','',4),(585,120,63,'','',5),(586,118,63,'','',6),(587,121,63,'','',7),(588,172,63,'','',8),(589,NULL,63,'','',9),(590,NULL,63,'','',10),(591,NULL,63,'','',11),(592,NULL,63,'','',12),(593,53,62,'<p>The Pictish people were a small tribe that lived around the rivers of Scotland. They lived in the time before the 10th century and it is unknown what they called themselves. &nbsp;We call them the Pict people because it&rsquo;s rooted from the Latin word \"picti\" which means painted or tattooed people. &nbsp;There is still a lot to be known about the Pict tribe, it is assumed that many of the members of this tribe were covered in tattoos, but there has been some discrepancy about how many of them actually carried tattoos. &nbsp;Many of the members of the tribe covered themselves in blue paint during wartime as a way of identifying each other on the battleground.</p>','',1),(594,59,62,'<p>This is one of many potrayals of the Picts dawning blue war paint on the battle ground.</p>','',2),(595,50,62,'<p><span>\"The Picts were known to have existed from about 7000 B.C. until about the year 845 A.D. An interesting feature of Pict society was that the crown was passed using a matrilineal basis; that is to say the crown was passed through the mother, and Pictish kings were not succeeded by their sons, but by their brothers or nephews or male cousins traced through the female line.\"</span></p>','',3),(596,108,62,'<p><span>\"The word \"Pict\" means \"painted people\", probably referring to the Pictish custom of either tattooing their bodies or embellishing themselves with \"warpaint\". However, their Irish term \"Cruithni\", meaning \"the people of the designs\", seems to parallel the Roman name, so it may be that \"Picti\" was an adaptation of the name they called themselves.\"</span></p>','',4),(597,51,62,'<p>Another depiction by the same artist of a Pict family bearing many different tattoos, even the young child.</p>','',5),(598,NULL,62,'','',6),(599,NULL,62,'','',7),(600,NULL,62,'','',8),(621,NULL,48,'','',3),(622,NULL,48,'','',4),(601,NULL,59,'','',10),(602,NULL,59,'','',11),(603,NULL,59,'','',12),(606,57,64,'<p>Around the 18th century when men from Europe began going on voyages and expeditions to Polynesia was the time that the tattoo started to become more of a widespread practice in the continent. &nbsp;Men started returning from their trips with tattoos and this created a demand for tattoos. &nbsp;In 1846 the first documented tattoo artist from Germany popped up in Massachusetts spending much of his time tattooing American Civil War soldiers, then the first documented British tattoo artist appeared in Liverpool. &nbsp;At this point tattoos were a very expensive commodity and had become a mark of wealth and crowned heads in Europe. &nbsp;The method of tattooing at this point was a modern one, but not yet fully evolutionized to what it is today. &nbsp;They used ink and sharp knives/tools in a safe way.</p>','',3),(607,190,64,'<p>The current practice and method of tattoos in Europe is the same that is used in most industrialized places in the world today. &nbsp;You go into a formal \"Tattoo Parlor\" and receive a tattoo from a professional using a tattoo gun. &nbsp;This tattoo gun combines the use of making tiny incisions and placing ink within those cuts at the same time.</p>\r\n<p>And even with the creation of the more safe tattoo gun, progressions are continuing to be made foward in the world of tattoing. &nbsp;People are always thriving to improve the tattoo gun to make it more sanitary as well as safer for the consumer. &nbsp;Even beyond the method of giving the tattoo is the method of getting them removed, up until a few years ago some people found themselves having to physically remove their skin in order to get rid of their tattoos. Now you are able to purchase a tattoo removal cream from most drug stores, a quite a steep price, that will in turn get rid of your body ink although it is not always guarenteed.&nbsp;</p>','',4),(608,NULL,64,'','',5),(609,NULL,64,'','',6),(610,NULL,64,'','',7),(611,NULL,64,'','',8),(612,54,65,'<p>This story comes from Lars Krutak in the article attacted to the image to the left.</p>\r\n<p>\"There are about a half-dozen tattooists working in Tirana today, but only four have their own shops. Some are just getting their start in the business, while others are old hands.</p>\r\n<p>At first, it is difficult to find them. There is nothing on the internet about them and although there is a&nbsp;<em>Yellow Pages</em>&nbsp;directory, &ldquo;Tattoo Shops&rdquo; are not listed even though they must be licensed and taxed by the government. The best plan of attack is to stop a young person on the street (or better yet someone with tattoos) to get directions or ask your local bartender, because you&rsquo;ll probably strike out, as I did initially, with taxi cab drivers.</p>\r\n<p>Most young people also speak some English, or at least Italian which is like a second language to them. So if you are not proficient in Albanian, which is one of the hardest languages in the world to speak because it&rsquo;s not related to any other, you better heed my advice!\"</p>','',1),(613,58,65,'<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>This is the story of how the Albanian Eagle became to be such a prevelant figure in the life of so many Albanians. &nbsp;Because of the power of the story and what this eagle means to the people of Albania, many citizens now have it tattooed somewhere on the body, most making it unique in their own way as too feel as if them too have a eagle watching over them.</p>\r\n<p>\"A young boy was hunting in the mountains. An eagle&nbsp;flying above him alighted on top of a crag. The eagle was especially large and had a snake&nbsp;in its beak. After a while, the eagle flew away from the crag where it had its nest. The small boy then climbed to the top of the crag where he saw, in the nest, an eaglet playing with the dead snake. But the snake wasn\'t really dead! Suddenly it stirred, revealed its fangs and was ready to pierce the eaglet with its deadly venom. The boy quickly took out his bow and arrow and killed the snake. Then he took the eaglet and started for his home. Suddenly the boy heard above him the loud whir of the great eagle\'s wings.</p>\r\n<p>\"Why do you kidnap my child?\" cried the eagle.</p>\r\n<p>\"The child is mine because I saved it from the snake which you didn\'t kill,\" answered the youth.</p>\r\n<p>\"Give me back my child, and I will give you as a reward the sharpness of my eyes and the powerful strength of my wings. You will become invincible, and you will be called by my name!\"</p>\r\n<p>Thus the young boy handed over the eaglet. After the eaglet grew, it would always fly above the head of the boy, now a grown man, who with his bow and arrows killed many wild beasts of the forest, and with his sword slew many enemies of the land. During all of these feats, the eagle faithfully watched over and guided him.</p>\r\n<p>Amazed by the valiant hunter\'s deeds, the people of the land elected him king and called him&nbsp;<em>Shqip&euml;tar</em>, which is to say&nbsp;<em>Son of the Eagle</em>&nbsp;and his kingdom became known as \"Shqip&euml;ria\" or&nbsp;<em>Land of the Eagles</em>.The two heads on the eagle represent the north and the south.\"</p>','',2),(614,201,65,'<p>\"Why do you kidnap my child?\" cried the eagle.</p>\r\n<p>\"The child is mine because I saved it from the snake which you didn\'t kill,\" answered the youth.</p>\r\n<p>\"Give me back my child, and I will give you as a reward the sharpness of my eyes and the powerful strength of my wings. You will become invincible, and you will be called by my name!\"</p>\r\n<p>Thus the young boy handed over the eaglet. After the eaglet grew, it would always fly above the head of the boy, now a grown man, who with his bow and arrows killed many wild beasts of the forest, and with his sword slew many enemies of the land. During all of these feats, the eagle faithfully watched over and guided him.</p>\r\n<p>Amazed by the valiant hunter\'s deeds, the people of the land elected him king and called him&nbsp;<em>Shqip&euml;tar</em>, which is to say&nbsp;<em>Son of the Eagle</em>&nbsp;and his kingdom became known as \"Shqip&euml;ria\" or&nbsp;<em>Land of the Eagles</em>.The two heads on the eagle represent the north and the south.\"</p>','',3),(615,NULL,65,'','',4),(616,NULL,65,'','',5),(617,NULL,65,'','',6),(618,NULL,65,'','',7),(619,NULL,65,'','',8),(623,NULL,48,'','',5),(624,NULL,48,'','',6),(625,NULL,48,'','',7),(626,NULL,48,'','',8),(628,200,66,'<p>Giannoula, the old woman pictured to the left was born in Albania and is one of very few of Vlachs living today. The origins of the Vlachs are quite strange and many agree that they are the last group of Latin-speaking population that existed in the Balkans since the Roman Empire. They had an unwritten language that is strange becasue it seems to be Latin based, unlike any Greek language. &nbsp;Towards the end of the 15th century that Vlachs seemed to have power in much of Greece until the Ottoman Empire came in and took over power for the next 600 years.</p>\r\n<p>Today the Vlachs make up an incredibly small population in an increasing Greek population. But they continue to wear their traditional dress, speak their unwritten language, and participate in ancient customs, including tattoo. Although increasingly rare, traditional tattoo exists on a handful of elder Vlach women. According to Giannoula, these marks affected powerful curses against the Evil Eye and other misfortunes. Also, her tattoos protected her from the ruling Turks, who considered woman with body tattoos as \"mutilated people.\" The Vlachs used carbon as the pigment of many of their tattoos, that is why you see them fading in the picture of Giannoula\'s hand.</p>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>','',2),(629,NULL,66,'','',3),(630,NULL,66,'','',4),(631,NULL,66,'','',5),(632,NULL,66,'','',6),(633,NULL,66,'','',7),(634,NULL,66,'','',8),(635,NULL,38,'','',9),(636,NULL,38,'','',10),(637,NULL,38,'','',11),(638,NULL,38,'','',12),(639,262,39,'','<p>A look at an early tattoo machine developed in the late 19th Century.</p>',2),(640,NULL,39,'','',3),(641,NULL,39,'','',4),(642,NULL,39,'','',5),(643,NULL,39,'','',6),(644,NULL,39,'','',7),(645,NULL,39,'','',8),(646,NULL,39,'','',9),(647,241,67,'','',1),(648,240,67,'','',2),(649,239,67,'','',3),(650,237,67,'','',4),(651,235,67,'','',5),(652,234,67,'','',6),(653,233,67,'','',7),(654,232,67,'','',8),(655,231,67,'','',9),(656,230,67,'','',10),(657,229,67,'','',11),(658,228,67,'','',12),(659,227,67,'','',13),(660,226,67,'','',14),(661,214,67,'','',15),(662,209,67,'','',16),(663,205,68,'','',1),(664,84,68,'','',2),(665,83,68,'','',3),(666,81,68,'','',4),(667,80,68,'','',5),(668,NULL,68,'','',6),(669,NULL,68,'','',7),(670,NULL,68,'','',8),(671,NULL,68,'','',9),(672,NULL,68,'','',10),(673,NULL,68,'','',11),(674,NULL,68,'','',12),(675,NULL,68,'','',13),(676,NULL,68,'','',14),(677,NULL,68,'','',15),(678,NULL,68,'','',16),(679,81,69,'<p>There exists a great deal of historical precedent for body art in the Middle East, from the dawn of civilization in the ancient world to the birth of Islam. The Egyptian culture has developed tattooing practices for at least four thousand years, making it the longest known history of tattooing. Similarly, artifacts from the Middle Kingdom and Nubia contain the second-oldest evidence of tattooing worldwide. The practice of tattooing in Arabia and the near east can be traced through the Persian imperial period, across Bedouin tribal generations, and amongst gypsy culture, lending continuity to the present day, albeit tempered by the rise of Islam, which holds provisions against the practice on the grounds of religious purity. Nevertheless, examples of tattooing flourish amidst the contemporary Muslim diaspora. Mehndi, as well, spread out of the Indian subcontintent and is commonly practiced amidst certain circles in the Arabian regions.</p>','',1),(680,83,70,'<p>A pair of techniques seem to have been largely employed in antiquity by Middle Eastern cultures to introduce tattoos below the skin. One method involved piercing the skin and drawing pigment-coated twine beneath it in the wake of a needle, while the other slightly more resembled the modern technique of piercing directly and allowing ink to pool underneath the skin forth from the piercing instrument. Contemporary tattoo parlors in the middle east typically leverage modern techniques.</p>\r\n<p>The practice of Mehndi focuses on the temporary application of henna paste to the surface of the skin, either with a cone or a brush, before a wrap is applied atop the paste to entrap its coloration upon the skin\'s surface. The stain on the surface lasts for a period of weeks, darkens with oxidation, and typically fades as a result of exfoliation.</p>','',1),(681,228,70,'','',2),(682,241,70,'','',3),(683,NULL,70,'','',4),(684,NULL,70,'','',5),(685,NULL,70,'','',6),(686,NULL,70,'','',7),(687,NULL,70,'','',8),(688,NULL,70,'','',9),(689,NULL,70,'','',10),(690,NULL,70,'','',11),(691,NULL,70,'','',12),(692,239,71,'<p>Tattooing and Mehndi have long held cultural relevance in both and artistic and spiritual sense, often with the two intertwined. Tattooed mummies uncovered in ancient Egypt were initially believed to be those of concubines or dancers of low social rank, but further research revealed that some of them were actually the remains of high-status members of the class of priests. Beduoin tribes in Arabia and the Berber tribes of north Africa both hold superstitions regarding the nature of tattoos as warding markings against occult forces. Contemporary recipients of tattoos often do so with the intent to signify ideas or events that are important to them, and it appears as if the tradition was no different in Middle Eastern antiquity, and has carried along throughout various tribal traditions - that the subject differs in accordance with world view should be no surprise.</p>','',1),(693,234,71,'','',2),(694,231,71,'','',3),(695,209,71,'','',4),(696,NULL,71,'','',5),(697,NULL,71,'','',6),(698,NULL,71,'','',7),(699,NULL,71,'','',8),(700,NULL,71,'','',9),(701,NULL,71,'','',10),(702,NULL,71,'','',11),(703,NULL,71,'','',12),(704,NULL,72,'<p><strong>References:</strong></p>\r\n<p><a class=\"download-file\" href=\"http://dh101.humanities.ucla.edu/DH101Fall12Lab5/archive/files/5dea9e77670bfbc8626b3837b112cdb4.pdf\">The Religious Significance of Women\'s Scarification among the Tiv</a></p>\r\n<p><a href=\"http://www.medicine.uottawa.ca/historyofmedicine/hetenyi/ayeni.htm#11\">Observations on the Medical and Social Aspects of Scarification in Sub-Saharan Africa</a></p>\r\n<p><a class=\"download-file\" href=\"http://dh101.humanities.ucla.edu/DH101Fall12Lab5/archive/files/893f4ee2ed582e3b10b83894ff04ae5c.pdf\">An Ancient Practice- Scarification and Tribal Marking in Ghana</a></p>\r\n<p><a class=\"download-file\" href=\"http://dh101.humanities.ucla.edu/DH101Fall12Lab5/archive/files/6f07ed7e83f23b50361292fb627d4c9a.pdf\">Beyond Diversity Women, Scarification, and Yoruba Identity</a></p>\r\n