INSERT INTO `omeka_sections` VALUES (1,'Tattoos of Samoa and Tonga','<p>There is a high importance of body art shared in the cultures of Samoa and Tonga. They follow many of the common trends of polynesian cultures, however each of them do have their own respective traditions. Out of all the pacific islands, Samoa and Tonga have the most similar design of the art, with only&nbsp;few noticeable differences. When looked at side by side, it may be nearly impossible to spot them, however there are a few characteristics that set the designs apart. Length is the most obvious, with Samoan pe\'a tattoos starting just below the knee and extending up the leg, and across the buttocks up to the torso. Tongan tattoos take the same shape but begin from just above the knee instead of below. Tongan design also features more solid black lines without detail. As Samoan pe\'a continues to develop from its initial traditional designs, the Tongan tatatau is a combination of past and present in hopes to bring the art back to life without forgetting the past.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>',2,1,'section-1'),(12,'2. War Inspiration','<p>Soldiers fighting for ideals greater than themselves revolutionized the practice of tattooing in the West, beginning with World War I.</p>',3,2,'war-inspiration'),(10,'1. Meaning Behind the Marks','<p>In African cultures, each social group defines its own rules about scarification. Scars are often specific to the community and based on the ancestors of the tribe. The markings also vary based on gender, age, social ranking, etc. By the time individuals reach adulthood, they will have recieve several sets of scars, each representing a stage of life or specific characteristic.&nbsp;Both men and women subjected themselves to these costly incisions because their societies placed such importance on the display of scar patterns. Scars indicated a person\'s rank and age in society.&nbsp;In many cultures, a woman\'s eagerness to bear the pain of scarification is an indication of emotional maturity and willingness to bear children. For men, it is often serves as record of personal accomplishments in war or hunting.&nbsp;</p>',1,1,'meaning-behind-the-marks'),(5,'4. Scarification Images','<p>This final section features the <em>images<strong></strong></em>&nbsp;collection of African body art.&nbsp;</p>',1,4,'scarification-images'),(6,'Tattoos','<p>Navigate through a collection of images of European tatoos dated all the way back to 3500 BC to pictures of current tattoos within this section.</p>',6,1,'tattoos'),(7,'History','<p><strong><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">History</span></strong></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;This history of tattooing and body art in Europe has been mainly concentrated into a few main cultures and areas.&nbsp; Greece, Scotland, Austria, and Albania; these areas have all had cultures with very rich and long-lived histories with tattoos.&nbsp; The Pict culture of Scotland saw tattoos as benefitting there lives in many different ways, they saw them as an incredibly aesthetically pleasing form of art, as well as a way of identifying themselves differently from other cultures.&nbsp; Some people also believe that the Picts saw tattoos as a form of camouflage during battle.&nbsp; In Albania, it is almost considered a staple thing in their culture to receive the tattoo of the Albanian Eagle.&nbsp; Its not always the exact same, some choose to put more details or small add on&rsquo;s.&nbsp; The eagle is one of two heads and is also found on the Albanian flag.&nbsp; Greece has a significant history because it is home to Europes first tattoo parlor, one that is still running today, and because of Greece is one of a Europe&rsquo;s prime hubs of tattooing.</p>',6,2,'history'),(8,'China','<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>The tattoo practices in China represent a variety of cultural traditions. Chinese tattooing began during the Zhou Dynasty, which was prevalent from 1045 BC to 256 BC. In ancient China tattooing was associated with gangs and bandits. The Qing dynasty beginning in the 17th century saw a shift in cultural meaning, viewing tattoos as an art form. One aspect that seems to set China apart from other tattooing regions is its\' involvement with facial tattooing. This is most common among women and has varying meanings within different Chinese tribes (see below for more information). Furthermore, diverse cultural meanings of tattoos reveal China as a very unique country when it comes to body art.</p>\r\n<p>Here we focus primarily on three different cultures of Chinese body art.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>1. Dulong (Derung):</strong>&nbsp;The women of the Dulong (also known as the Derung) tribe have been practicing the ancient art of facial tattooing for many decades. While there is some discrepancy in the precise origin of this tradition, many believe in it as a source of protection as well as a sign of maturity. Girls began receiving facial tattoos when they were 12 or 13 years old to represent that they were coming of age. Women of the Derung tribe were often captured and taken as slaves, and sometimes raped. The tribe began tattooing girls faces in an effort to make them less beautiful, and therefore less desirable to potential predators. Over the years, the tradition has started to cease and finally it was abolished as a tribal practice in 1967. Today, there are still about 50 Derung women with facial tattoos.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>2. Li:</strong> The tattooing practices of the Li tribe represents woman coming of age. They are often tattooed along their neck (usually nape), shoulders, or face. This process occurs when they are 11 or 12 and usually takes about 5 days. According to ethnologist Hans St&uuml;bel, the origin of Li tattooing lay in legend: &ldquo;The progenitor of the Li had a daughter, whose mother died shortly after the birth of this child. Whereupon a hoopoe (Upupa epops) fed the child with grains. In remembrance, the Li women still tattoo themselves in order to appear to be as colorful as birds. Perhaps, the tattoos should represent the pattern on the wings of the hoopoes.&rdquo; This adds an interesting insight when observing the often geometrical tattooing patterns of these women. Furthermore, the Li believed that women were not to tattoo their hands until they were married. Marriage often was accompanied by the decoration of the backs of their hands.</p>\r\n<p><strong>3. Dai:</strong>&nbsp;The Dai civilization holds tattooing a highly important practice for both men and women. In ancient times, Dai children as young as the age of 5 or 6 were tattooed, but it has grown more common over time for this practice be delayed until the age of 14 or 15 instead. The Dai people see tattoos as a sign of both strength and virility, especially among Dai men where they are often placed to accentuate muscles.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>The final page (labeled<strong> 4.&nbsp;</strong><strong>Historical Overview</strong>) includes items that give an overall history without specifically describing one of these civilizations.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>',4,1,'china'),(11,'1. Contemporary Body Art','<p>How tattoos have shaped society today and how they are perceived. &nbsp;Are they safe? &nbsp;Are they professional? &nbsp;Are they accepted by the media and modern culture?</p>',3,1,'contemporary-body-art'),(13,'3. Origin of Western Tattoos','<p>The diffusion of tattoo practice to the Americas beginning with the Pacific influence in the late 18th Century.</p>',3,3,'origin-of-western-tattoos'),(14,'Methodology','<p><strong><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">Methodology</span></strong></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;The methodology of tattooing was very different around the world at first. &nbsp;But as many different cultures and countries began going on voyages and settling elsewhere many places picked up on safer and more effective ways of preforming the art. &nbsp;The Europeans had the most advanced way that they were able to spread to places such as Oceania and to the Maori tribe in specific. &nbsp;The Europeans would use sharp metal tools to make the incisions and then ink compared to the Maori who used sharp bone and a combination of things as their ink.&nbsp; One of the most questioned things in the method and practice of tattoos in Europe is how Otzi the Iceman was able to tattoo himself and then have the tattoos remain there for thousands of years.&nbsp; It is thought that he used ink primarily made of berries and made the incisions with a sharp tool.&nbsp; The current practice is one that has been globalized which is the use of the tattoo gun.&nbsp;</p>',6,3,'methodology'),(15,'Anthropology','<div class=\"WordSection1\">\r\n<p><strong><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">Anthropology:</span></strong></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;The Anthropology of tattoos in Europe is one of rich and diverse history.&nbsp; It is apparent that it started as early as 3500 BC in the Otzal Alpes of Austria with the discovery of Otzi the Iceman.&nbsp; This discovery has proven to be a huge deal for people who study the history of body art, but from an anthropological scale it is only a small sliver of everything that has happened from that time until now.&nbsp; The practice of body art has greatly transformed in Europe, it began being used as a way to relief pain in the joints, now use could range from a memoriam for a family member to a representation of a violent crime organization that the given individual is a part of. The use of body art has held a number of different implications in its many years of practice, explore and learn about them all.</p>\r\n</div>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>',6,4,'anthropology'),(16,'Japan','<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Japanese tattoos date back to 3000 BC. Archaeologists have discovered Japanese tombs from this time that have clay figurines covered in tattoo art. These figurines have become known as \'dogu,\' and historians believe that the dogu represent individuals who were living at one time. In the 17th century, tattoos began to have a negative connotation, as they became associated with the lower class and criminals. At the beginning of the Meiji period (around 1868) the Japanese government outlawed tattoos, trying to protect a more sacred image of their country. This in turn, reinforced the pre-existing idea of tattoos marking criminals. Tattooing was legalized in 1948, but the image of criminality associated with the art form remains. Moreover, the traditional Japanese word for tattoos is \"irezumi.\" Over time, this has come to be understood as a tattoo of which the subject matter is traditional Japanese, whereas the word \"tattoo\" is describes the body art of non-Japanese designs. Irezumi full body suits (traditionally covering the arms, back, upper legs, and chest) are fairly popular not only in Japan, but also in Western nations. Body suits are culturally Japanese because they are traditionally made to look like a kimono. Moreover, Japan\'s history is a bit more stagnant that that of other nations. Although it dates back to early times, the practice has not been able to shake the reputation of criminality.</p>',4,2,'japan'),(17,'Tattoos of New Zealand','<p>The Maori people of New Zealand &ndash; or Aotearoa as they call it &ndash; feature some of the most rich tattooing traditions. The Maori designs are very recognizable and are often copied and mimicked. Since the earliest days, the most traditional Maori tattoo is full-face ta moko. This tattoo on men covers nearly the entire face and on women generally just on the chin. Acquiring the moko often represents ones entering of adulthood, but can carry other meanings as well. Through the traditional polynesian methods, the moko tattoos embed a natural pigment in to the skin, one tap at a time using handmade tools. This painstaking process still doesn\'t stop even the Maori\'s of today from getting their own personal moko.</p>\r\n<p><br /><br /></p>',2,2,'new-zealand'),(18,'General History','<p>This section includes items that describe Asian tattoo practices as a whole, rather than just focusing on China or Japan.&nbsp;</p>',4,3,'general-history'),(19,'2. Methodology','<p>Traditional African scarification is a painful, extensive process. Extraordinarily integral to these tribal communities, &nbsp;the ritual performed by the local the scarmaster determines as childs first scars as well as that will be added throughout their lifetime. The profession of scarmaster is generally passed down from parent to child as they teach them&nbsp;the complexities and dangers of working with blades and human skin. This section focuses on the tools used in the scarification processes as well as the importance of the scarification ritual.&nbsp;</p>',1,2,'methodology'),(20,'3. Scarification: Change Over Time','<p>Over time, significant events such as civil war and the introduction of slave trade have played a huge role in the evolution of scarification, changing both its purpose and overall importance. In recent years, much attention has been brought to scarification, questioning its importance and claiming the practice as inhumane. In several regions of Africa, local governments has outlawed or banned on terms of brutality. However, it has been popularized into a form of body art that is offered in tattoo shops around the world.</p>',1,3,'scarification-change-over-time'),(21,'Pacific Island Tattoo Traditions','<p>There are many shared processes between the polynesian cultures. This section highlights the craft of the unique tools they use as well as the the methods of tattoo application. While some of the cultures have overlapping traditions, others standalone as truly unique. With the incorporation of prayers and ritual throughout every step of the process, tattooing in pacific island culture remains to be a sacred act.</p>',2,3,'pacific-island-tattoo-process'),(22,'Gallery','<p>A gallery containing a variety of images related to tattooing, Mehndi, and other forms of body decoration in the Near East, Middle East, and Ancient World.</p>',5,1,'gallery'),(23,'History','<p>An examination of the history of body art in the Middle East with a particular consideration given to the ancient world.</p>',5,2,'history'),(24,'Methodology','<p>An examination of the various methods of body art employed in both antiquity and modern times across the Middle East.</p>',5,3,'methodology'),(25,'Anthropology','<p>An examination of the culture and traditions of body art in the Middle East, with particular consideration given to tribal influences.</p>',5,4,'anthropology'),(26,'5. Reference','<p>This section is a list of references used in the composition of this exhibit.</p>',1,5,'references');
