INSERT INTO `omeka_simple_pages_pages` VALUES (1,4,3,1,0,'About the Project','about','<p><strong>The process:</strong></p>\r\n<p>This project takes a look through an anthropological lense at body art around the world, observing the cultural aspect of tattooing. Body art has various traditions, meanings, and methodologies associated with it based on varying locations and cultures. In our project, we aim to explore these different meanings within the cultural context of tattooing and scarification.</p>\r\n<p>We have chosen to break down our topic by location, focusing on the six major regions where tattooing is prominent or has a unique history. We have dedicated our exhibits to the historical and cultural details of body art in the following six regions: Africa, Asia, Europe, Middle East, North America, and the Pacific Islands</p>\r\n<p>Our goal is to a resource site that is easily accessible and that well-represents the various types of body art found across the word.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<hr />\r\n<p><strong>Group Members:&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Lindsie Levinson -&nbsp;<a title=\"Africa\" href=\"http://dh101.humanities.ucla.edu/DH101Fall12Lab5/exhibits/show/africa\" target=\"_self\">Africa</a></li>\r\n<li>Wendy Siino - <a title=\"Asia\" href=\"http://dh101.humanities.ucla.edu/DH101Fall12Lab5/exhibits/show/asia\" target=\"_self\">Asia</a></li>\r\n<li>Daniel Ross - <a title=\"Pacific Island and Oceania\" href=\"http://dh101.humanities.ucla.edu/DH101Fall12Lab5/exhibits/show/pacific-islands-and-oceania\" target=\"_self\">Pacific Islands and Oceania</a></li>\r\n<li>Stephen Youts - <a title=\"Middle East\" href=\"http://dh101.humanities.ucla.edu/DH101Fall12Lab5/exhibits/show/middle-east\" target=\"_self\">Middle East</a></li>\r\n<li>Max Sieck - <a title=\"Europe\" href=\"http://dh101.humanities.ucla.edu/DH101Fall12Lab5/exhibits/show/europe\" target=\"_self\">Europe</a></li>\r\n<li>Matt Fisher - <a title=\"North America\" href=\"http://dh101.humanities.ucla.edu/DH101Fall12Lab5/exhibits/show/north-america\" target=\"_self\">North America</a></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<hr />\r\n<p><strong>Personal Reflection:&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>Lindsie Levinson:</strong></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;I&rsquo;ll start with letting it be known that I have had no previous experience whatsoever in html or any sort of content management systems coming into this project so I am very proud of this outcome! Intimidated and overwhelmed, I decided to give this project my best shot. The first feat was understanding how to actually manage my content and working with my wonderful group to figure out how we wanted to standardize and categorize our materials. Once we had a solid basis as to what we would each focus on, researching and adding my items with the corresponding metadata did not seem so bad. I actually really enjoyed learning about African Body Art.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp; After completing all of my items, the limitations of Omeka are what frustrated me the most. In terms of the interface, I would have loved to change colors, font sizes, etc, but given these limitations along with my lack of any expertise computer science that could override such limits, I was unable to do so. Creativity is where I thrive so this drove me absolutely crazy. After finally giving up on getting all things creative, I decided my only choice was to settle with one of the given themes provided by Omeka. My next biggest frustration came in dealing with neatline, which was completely over my head. But as we began to work as a group was trying the handle the timeline/map as a whole it started to come together. I guess the age old saying two heads is better than one is true. After getting a grasp of neatline, we were about to produce both a timeline and a map, however I think our struggle is evident in its presentation. We still had some troubles with establishing a set view as both seem to be extremely zoomed in.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp; Overall, it took me a while to become familiar with Omeka in creating my Africa exhibit. After reviewing my exhibit with David, I decided to go back to square one and reorganize and create a more consistent narrative through my sections and pages within my exhibit that tells all about African body art. I have to note here: why doesn\'t omeka have spell check! This drove me absolutely crazy. This just seems like something that Omeka should include. This project took lots of writing and rewriting and lots of copy and pasting from word; in three separate attempts of creating and deleting exhibits, I have finally created an exhibit that I am happy with.&nbsp;The next step of creating this site was figuring out how to organize the presentation of information. We decided to use the home page as navigation by clicking each photo (with the country written on it) to redirect to the exhibit. We struggled with figuring out how to construct the navigation bar at the top. After trying out a few different options (we were trying to get fancy) I came up with the idea of using symbols, we ended up using the /, to separate home from the countries and from the visualizations.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>In dealing with all of the limitations and requirement in Omeka, I have learned an extraordinary amount about content management and display as well as about my topic (African Body Art Master at your service).&nbsp;After this experience I have to thank the members of my group who helped make this site possible. I am very impressed every single one you! We have created something that I think we can all say we are very proud of! Bravo, let&rsquo;s all go get tattoos together now.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong><br /></strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>Wendy Siino:</strong></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;I do not have much experience with content management systems, yet the frustration I experienced with Omeka was plentiful. For one thing, the lack of spell check is extremely aggravating. Also, there is too much modularity with each item&mdash;there should be a way to check a handful of items and mass edit them (in instances such as geo-tagging the location or making an item public). Another issue with Omeka&nbsp;is the interface. I think that there should be a distinction between account settings and website settings. This would make it much easier to edit and control tabs and such. Being able to add drop down menus would also be helpful. It would be very helpful if you could edit the site while looking at the public site view, such as how iWeb operates. Being able to drag and manipulate various entities directly would make this process much more enjoyable. Lastly, the limit on item sizes was a huge problem for me and inhibited me from adding some items that I feel could have really added a lot to my exhibit.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;A second key area of struggle was with Neatline. It is created very counter intuitively through the item section and the mapping device is much too specific. While its nice that it allows the user to determine the ambiguity with regards to dates, it would have been very helpful to be able to do this with location as well.&nbsp;Neatline also fails to save the zoomed out view of the map to the public site.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;The timeline on Neatline was where my frustration peaked. First I tried simply to check the items I wanted added to the timeline, while some items would appear on the line, others would not, despite having consistent meta data. I then tried a different approach by creating new items and then solely adding them to the timeline and not the map. While this method worked, it required us to add new items rather than using existing. The timeline also failed to zoom out automatically on the public site.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;There were also some positive aspects of working with Omeka. For one thing, it coerced me to learn to work within predetermined boundaries. Also, its metadata features are quite extensive and well done. Furthermore, working with a group helped further foster leadership and communication skills. It forced me to realize that each individual has a specific set of skills and when each member contributed their special skill, we accomplished great things. All in all, while this project did result in some frustration and rather high amounts of profanity, it taught me quite a bit and the amount of pride I feel when looking at the outcome is immeasurable.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><a title=\"Asia\" href=\"http://dh101.humanities.ucla.edu/DH101Fall12Lab5/exhibits/show/asia\" target=\"_self\"><br /></a><strong>Daniel Ross:</strong></p>\r\n<p>This project was both exciting and frustrating for me. I was excited to finally get to work on a project in college, because I went to high school with a project-based curriculum. I also liked the idea of the project because I enjoy building websites and graphic design. I feel like I have learned a lot about building databases and digital humanities sites, however I was not thrilled with the limitations of Omeka. The limited themes available to use as well as the cookie-cutter format they force you to use make it easy to create a site, but hard to truly design it from the bottom up. As a content manager, Omeka is a useful tool. There are just a few kinks that need to be worked out to expedite the process of building and managing a database with ease.</p>\r\n<p>Throughout the project, my role was to build the Pacific Islands exhibit. I specifically enjoyed researching this region because my mom is from New Zealand and I have spent a lot of time there. New Zealand is the research that definitely came easiest. The Maori tattooing culture is alive as ever and there was an abundance of information to gather and share. The Samoan and Tongan cultures were a little trickier to find because the art had fallen off a little bit because of missionaries. Once the data was gathered, I didn\'t find many troubles posting them to the Omeka site other than the tediousness. An improvement for Omeka would be to allow items to be uploaded directly from their source, and also allow for editing multiple items at once. The majority of the struggles I did have were from working on the settings, plugins and design of the site. Our site underwent a design change over the last couple days of work time because of the troubles that we had with plugins. We initially wanted to feature a Neatline map directly on our homepage, however the lack of features that plugin offers made us change our mind. I helped head the redesign by contributing the graphic design work as well as some of the site formatting. With the CSS expertise of Stephen, we were able to get our site looking how we wanted in the end.</p>\r\n<p>Overall, I did enjoy this project. I now know quite a decent amount about the body art of the world &ndash; pacific islands especially, and have had the opportunity to build my first database. I\'ve enjoyed working with my group and I am proud of our final product.</p>\r\n<p><strong><br />Stephen Youts:</strong></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;As a student of computer science with relative little background in the humanities, this project proved an interesting challenge for me on the non-technical level, and intellectually interesting in the sense that it fuses humanistic inquiry with some amount of technical endeavor. I was quite familiar with content management systems prior to my introduction to Omeka, and have a background in programmatic web development and design, as well, so it was relatively easy to get up-to-speed with the system after a cursory examination. My experience with Omeka was one of both initial ease and irritating inflexibility; there were several things we wished to do with the project that proved impossible due to the nature of the CMS and our limited access to server resources. We were also able to work around some challenges.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp; The greatest technical challenges largely arose due to the need to work within the constraints of the Omeka framework - implementing the image-based navigation on the front page necessitated the use of some irritating inline JavaScript and CSS, which is typically frowned upon in web development, and the desire to integrate a more well-organized appealing timeline solution than what Neatline is able to offer, which unfortunately failed due to a lack of control over the software and the unwillingness to pay for a third-party solution for embedding in the site.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp; Non-technically, I found the project to be fairly insightful with regard to considering digital humanities issues in the context of the actual design of exhibits and the aggregation of information into an appropriate medium. Nevertheless, I grew quite frustrated with the time spent actually procuring and curating content, which I feel might have been better spent on a more analytical pursuit that encourages more dynamic thinking. Whether this is a reflection of our chosen topic over the premise of the project itself is something I have not yet ascertained. I did find it difficult to collect enough information about my topic to really put together a compelling exhibit - curiously, there is a reasonable amount of textual information, but searching the visual history of body art in the Middle East seems obfuscated by modern bastardizations and orientalisms, particularly with respect to Egyptian tattooing practices, investigation into which more often than not yielded faux-hieroglyphic results.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp; I felt constrained in the context of design, as well, due to the lack of access to the markup documents for the site, and consequently consideration given to Schneider\'s eight principles perhaps did not reflect as well as it might in the final product. Nevertheless, small considerations such as splitting the navigation bar with slash characters to cluster sub-topics of information without obfuscating them behind a second layer of navigation proved viable.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp; Overall, the experience was positive, although I do wish that we had greater flexibility both in terms of overall approach to the topic and with regard to the technology employed. Understandably, this may reflect more on my web development background and general irritations with feeling unduly constrained by the software than the nature of the project, but I still wish we had access to a greater number of features to realize a more unique and sleek vision for the interface. Ultimately I appreciate the diligent work of my team and the lessons we collectively learned in working on the project beyond any of my individual frustrations, however.</p>\r\n<p><strong><a title=\"Middle East\" href=\"http://dh101.humanities.ucla.edu/DH101Fall12Lab5/exhibits/show/middle-east\" target=\"_self\"><br /></a>Max Sieck:</strong></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;In my experience with this project I have found that my knowledge and ability to function with Omeka has increased greatly, but I have struggled in the way that I would like to customize things in a way that Omeka doesn&rsquo;t allow.&nbsp; The content management system has created a sense of automation that works both in favor and against the user.&nbsp; It makes is easy to manage and organize your items and collections within in the site, but at the same time it can make it incredibly dificult for you to organize it in a way that pleases you.&nbsp; With a little extra time I could see how it would be possible to work around things like that within the system, but coming into the class with minimal knowledge about how the system and computers as a whole work to do this impaired and set me back more than average.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp; I also found it difficult to really become familiar with many hands on digital humanities skills when I had to spend such a large amount of time focusing on my topic and transcribing great amounts of information into the site.&nbsp; I just felt as if it was more unnecessary knowledge than necessary. Although I did face a few challenges along the way with Omeka and my overall experience wasn&rsquo;t necessarily the best, I did find myself significantly improving with the use of Omeka and my abilities to work with a number of different Digital Humanities tools. Also working so closely with things such as metadata, data visualizations, building my own exhibit, helping contribute to the map and timeline, did really help with the formation and building of my skills in that area as well as helping me better understand all the basic principles. This project also benefited my ability to work together in groups considering this is the first time I have had to do so since I arrived at UCLA.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp; Lastly, having nothing to do with Omeka, I found it somewhat difficult to collect a satisfactory amount of information about my topic.&nbsp; Don&rsquo;t get me wrong I entered a lot, but I also feel as if a lot of it is repeated due to a lack of history and background in Europe.&nbsp; Much of the practice of tattooing originated and stayed in places like Africa and The Pacific Islands until Europeans began making Voyages there in the late 18<sup>th</sup> Century.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp; Although I had some struggles along the way, I did see this project a very beneficiary to the progress of my digital humanities knowledge and skills and I hope that you can see that as well.</p>\r\n<p><a title=\"Europe\" href=\"http://dh101.humanities.ucla.edu/DH101Fall12Lab5/exhibits/show/europe\" target=\"_self\"><br /></a><strong>Matt Fisher:</strong></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp; This project has been a very enlightening and inspiring experience for me.&nbsp; There have been many ways in which it has helped me improve and even create numerous invaluable academic skill sets such as data mining, research skills, group collaboration, website compilation, and more.&nbsp; It is extremely rewarding to put significant effort into a project and to be able to feel proud of the end result in only a short nine weeks.&nbsp; Coming from a background with next to zero experience in the digital world before this class, I have been amazed with how much I could quickly learn and put into practice.&nbsp; At the inception of the quarter I never expected to be able to stare at a multifaceted website of my own creation (in part).</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp; I have learned much more concerning our topic than I anticipated when the project was assigned.&nbsp; I would like to consider myself somewhat of a master, or at the least an educated scholar in the field of tattoos and more specifically North American tattoos.&nbsp; I have learned how to take a potentially colloquial topic and gather the tools to assess it through a cultural and scholarly lens.&nbsp; I have enjoyed the research I have compiled and have even been entertained by the majority of my findings; I have learned how to compile and sort through an assortment of metadata. It was particularly interesting to analyze statistics that relate to my life, for example the percentage of young adults with tattoos or the correlation between tattoos and grades among college students.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp; On the converse side of becoming such an expert on my topic, I do feel like the emphasis of the project could have been shifted a bit, though this may be a byproduct of the Omeka interface.&nbsp; Omeka is very straightforward and academic, but because of this it does not permit as much room for creativity as it could.&nbsp; I have become very familiar with navigating Omeka&rsquo;s site and adding items, but I cannot say I would be comfortable doing the same on a different interface.&nbsp; Also, Omeka is very constrictive in terms of display options, which is not conducive to a hands-on understanding of digital layout.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp; All in all I have thoroughly enjoyed my experience throughout the duration of the project.&nbsp; Many things I have learned will continue to be applicable in other classes and facets of my life.&nbsp; The only concern I express is that I have been more exposed to data and analysis of the tattoo industry than I have to experience in the digital world.&nbsp; However, I ultimately have a finished project that I am very proud of and have enjoyed every step of the way with my teammates.&nbsp;</p>','2012-12-06 23:32:17','2012-10-19 18:54:00',1,0,'',1),(9,3,6,1,0,'Data Visualization','data-visualization','<p><img src=\"http://dh101.humanities.ucla.edu/DH101Fall12Lab5/archive/files/67f115d1dc8f0e2d571ccd7c8f96128f.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"50\" /></p>\r\n<p>After examining body art around the world and over time, we take a look at present day opinions on contemporary body art including feeling, purpose, and meaning behind the tattoos.&nbsp;The following charts reveal data collected from <a href=\"http://www.statisticbrain.com/tattoo-statistics/\">\"Statistics Brain\"</a>, divulging statistics collected about tattooing practices in the United States. This data sheds light on the more physiological and psychological aspects of body art practices. While the exhibits focus on the cultural understanding and regional differences and traditions, these visualizations help convey the reality of tattoos as we (as Americans) often think of them.</p>\r\n<p><img src=\"http://dh101.humanities.ucla.edu/DH101Fall12Lab5/archive/files/c72349979b4d50d820d7ffc39411514e.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"700\" height=\"950\" /></p>','2012-11-30 08:47:21','2012-11-27 20:47:10',5,0,'',1),(11,3,6,1,0,'Feedback','feedback','<p><iframe src=\"https://docs.google.com/a/bitsofirreverence.com/spreadsheet/embeddedform?formkey=dF95a3NZdE0tR0g2b0ZybGFwQ25VZUE6MQ\" frameborder=\"0\" marginwidth=\"0\" marginheight=\"0\" width=\"760\" height=\"845\"></iframe></p>','2012-11-30 08:46:54','2012-11-28 21:30:28',3,0,'',1),(14,3,4,1,0,'Home','home-page','<p><a href=\"http://dh101.humanities.ucla.edu/DH101Fall12Lab5/exhibits/show/middle-east\"><img style=\"position: relative; left: 0px;\" onmouseover=\"this.src = \'http://dh101.humanities.ucla.edu/DH101Fall12Lab5/archive/files/1fc9ca9e297f7462addffc45c1a37bec.jpg\'\" onmouseout=\"this.src = \'http://dh101.humanities.ucla.edu/DH101Fall12Lab5/archive/files/342cae1222f471fad04ea0c933223aef.jpg\'\" src=\"http://dh101.humanities.ucla.edu/DH101Fall12Lab5/archive/files/342cae1222f471fad04ea0c933223aef.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"378\" height=\"226\" /></a> <a href=\"http://dh101.humanities.ucla.edu/DH101Fall12Lab5/exhibits/show/asia\"><img style=\"position: relative; top: -40px;\" onmouseover=\"this.src = \'http://dh101.humanities.ucla.edu/DH101Fall12Lab5/archive/files/e3b8851cdd94b0becf7b18144bf731e7.jpg\'\" onmouseout=\"this.src = \'http://dh101.humanities.ucla.edu/DH101Fall12Lab5/archive/files/062410b17bd5574a68f4ea28995c59e4.jpg\'\" src=\"http://dh101.humanities.ucla.edu/DH101Fall12Lab5/archive/files/062410b17bd5574a68f4ea28995c59e4.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"167\" height=\"221\" /></a> <a href=\"http://dh101.humanities.ucla.edu/DH101Fall12Lab5/exhibits/show/africa\"><img style=\"position: relative; top: -230px; left: 384px;\" onmouseover=\"this.src = \'http://dh101.humanities.ucla.edu/DH101Fall12Lab5/archive/files/62c613682f4f716fb8b34396ec93e80e.jpg\'\" onmouseout=\"this.src = \'http://dh101.humanities.ucla.edu/DH101Fall12Lab5/archive/files/1b8dbbd8ed20679dc9e672ccfe0e649e.jpg\'\" src=\"http://dh101.humanities.ucla.edu/DH101Fall12Lab5/archive/files/1b8dbbd8ed20679dc9e672ccfe0e649e.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"193\" height=\"257\" /></a> <a href=\"http://dh101.humanities.ucla.edu/DH101Fall12Lab5/exhibits/show/europe\"><img style=\"position: relative; top: -305px; left: 165px;\" onmouseover=\"this.src = \'http://dh101.humanities.ucla.edu/DH101Fall12Lab5/archive/files/fb368060194300afe63cec77fa301c6d.jpg\'\" onmouseout=\"this.src = \'http://dh101.humanities.ucla.edu/DH101Fall12Lab5/archive/files/a54ff063462b06f1a262c36edf83a700.jpg\'\" src=\"http://dh101.humanities.ucla.edu/DH101Fall12Lab5/archive/files/a54ff063462b06f1a262c36edf83a700.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"210\" height=\"222\" /></a> <a href=\"http://dh101.humanities.ucla.edu/DH101Fall12Lab5/exhibits/show/north-america\"><img style=\"position: relative; top: -490px; left: 170px;\" onmouseover=\"this.src = \'http://dh101.humanities.ucla.edu/DH101Fall12Lab5/archive/files/f94a6e726b1fada7737b9ea2492dabb3.jpg\'\" onmouseout=\"this.src = \'http://dh101.humanities.ucla.edu/DH101Fall12Lab5/archive/files/26ee92dc8fc6b0c40fb5d6c234fbaff0.jpg\'\" src=\"http://dh101.humanities.ucla.edu/DH101Fall12Lab5/archive/files/26ee92dc8fc6b0c40fb5d6c234fbaff0.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"173\" height=\"260\" /></a> <a href=\"http://dh101.humanities.ucla.edu/DH101Fall12Lab5/exhibits/show/pacific-islands-and-oceania\"><img style=\"position: relative; top: -500px; left: 374px;\" onmouseover=\"this.src = \'http://dh101.humanities.ucla.edu/DH101Fall12Lab5/archive/files/8ee33f6e6679b3c180533d3ac2ce337c.jpg\'\" onmouseout=\"this.src = \'http://dh101.humanities.ucla.edu/DH101Fall12Lab5/archive/files/af304e82edc4288943ac7caa35f3b6f2.jpg\'\" src=\"http://dh101.humanities.ucla.edu/DH101Fall12Lab5/archive/files/af304e82edc4288943ac7caa35f3b6f2.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"368\" height=\"190\" /></a></p>\r\n<p style=\"position: relative; top: -510px;\">This project takes a look through an anthropological lense at body art around the world, observing the cultural aspect of tattooing. Body art has various traditions, meanings, and methodologies associated with it based on varying locations and cultures. In our project, we aim to explore these different meanings within the cultural context of tattooing and scarification.</p>\r\n<p style=\"position: relative; top: -510px;\">We have chosen to break down our topic by location, focusing on the six major regions where tattooing is prominent or has a unique history. We have dedicated our exhibits to the historical and cultural details of body art in the following six regions: Africa, Asia, Europe, Middle East, North America, and the Pacific Islands. To view each region click the pictures above or the links at the top of the page.</p>','2012-11-30 08:43:29','2012-11-29 21:43:57',0,0,'',1);
